<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-89 0138EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-LostFish     07-15 0437</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lost Fish,0451</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fish Escapes After Marathon Battle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SOLDOTNA, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bob Ploeger will have a well-documented
fish story to tell when he gets back home to Minnesota.
   As with most fish stories, it will be about the one that got away.
   But this one is on the record. Ploeger attracted the attention of
local news photographers and hundreds of onlookers as he battled a
king salmon for nearly a day and a half before losing the fish and
perhaps a world record.
   The length of the struggle coupled with the way the fish dragged
boats up, down and across the river prompted speculation that it
might have been the king of kings, the sport-caught salmon that
finally would top the 100-pound mark.
   Kings that big have been caught commercially in Cook Inlet near
the mouth of the Kenai, but the biggest ever taken on a rod and reel
was 97 pounds, 4 ounces.
   The struggle began just after noon Wednesday when the 63-year-old
Ploeger, a retired jailer from Sandstone, Minn., hooked the fish
about four miles upstream from the Soldotna Bridge in south-central
Alaska about 75 miles southwest of Anchorage.
   Ploeger was fishing from a drift boat with a rookie guide, Dan
Bishop.
   Ploeger and Bishop soon abandoned the drift boat, hopping aboard
a passing powerboat after Bishop was unable to maneuver adequately
through some boulder-studded rapids.
   He fought the fish that quickly was dubbed the ``Boss Hog''
through the night and all day Thursday.
   As word of the fish spread, the crowds grew. Local restaurants
and businesses offered food and drink to Ploeger and the people
helping him. Other guides shuttled fuel to the boat.
   Ploeger said there were hours of boredom punctuated by
heart-stopping runs when the fish decided to go somewhere else.
   At one point, they thought they had him.
   ``He started coming up,'' said Pat Cooper, another guide
recruited along the way. ``We thought he was worn out, but he must
have gotten scared by the net.''
   By Thursday evening, the shoreline was lined with people. Some
brought lawn chairs, others fished themselves. At 8:36 p.m. they
erupted in cheers when it seemed a world record had been set for the
longest battle with a sport fish.
   According to the Guiness Book of World Records, a fisherman took
32{ hours to land a 1,600-pound marlin in New Zealand. Ploeger had
that beat _ if he could land the fish.
   But about four hours later, in the murky twilight that passes for
night during Alaska summers, the fish escaped _ leaving Ploeger and
everyone else wondering how big it really was.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
