<FIRST>r a AM-GuardInjuries     07-15 0183</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Guard Injuries,0185</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guard Troops Injured When Storm Flattens Tents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TRINIDAD, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 100 soldiers in National Guard units
from Kansas and Missouri were injured when a storm hit during war
games at the Pinon Canyon Maneuvers Site, officials said Friday.
   Sgt. Robert Aguilar of the Las Animas County sheriff's office
said the injuries ranged from scrapes, cuts and bruises to a few
broken bones and concussions. The most seriously injured were flown
to a hospital at nearby Fort Carson, he said.
   The soldiers were injured when winds, accompanied by rain and
small hail, flattened between 12 and 15 tents with troops inside, he
said. A half inch of rain and winds up to 50 and 60 mph were
reported, and there were unconfirmed reports of a tornado, Aguilar
said.
   Maj. Joy Moser, a public affairs officer for the 105th
Detachment, Kansas Army National Guard, said the storm hit about 3
p.m. and moved over the 562nd Support Group, U.S. Army Reserve Group
and the 82nd Field Hospital.
   He said the injured were evacuated because the field hospital
blew down.
</TEXT>
