<FIRST>r w PM-HUDProbe Bjt   07-15 0595</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-HUD Probe, Bjt,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aide Claims `Silent Sam' Spoke Up on HUD Projects</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY DENISE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top aide to former Housing Secretary Samuel
Pierce disputes Pierce's sworn claim that he had no direct role in
deciding what projects the scandal-scarred agency funded.
   Former HUD Assistant Secretary for Housing Shirley McVay Wiseman
also says Carla Hills, currently the U.S. trade representative,
lobbied Pierce to lift restrictions on a mortgage lender now under
federal criminal investigation.
   Hills is scheduled to testify before the committee on Monday.
   Wiseman said in sworn testimony Friday that Pierce personally
called her and instructed her to approve more than $15 million in
funding for a Durham, N.C., project sought by a former Pierce law
partner.
   Pierce said: ``I want the project funded,'' Wiseman told the
House Government Operations subcommittee on employment and housing,
one of three congressional panels investigating mismanagement and
fraud at the housing agency.
   The HUD approval brought more than $11.3 million in rent
subsidies, a $2.3 million grant and more than $3 million in tax
credits to developers who were seeking to turn a hosiery mill into
an apartment complex, said Rep. Tom Lantos, D-Calif., chairman of
the subcommittee.
   Pierce has testified he set up a three-person panel to make
funding decisions for the moderate rehabilitation program, but said
he maintained ``final authority'' over the decisions.
   ``I did not plan, however, to get into the decision-making
process of the panel when there was no complaint to justify my doing
so,'' he told the subcommittee in May.
   Efforts by The Associated Press to reach Pierce for comment were
unsuccessful. Lantos said he would seek to recall Pierce to the
subcommittee before the congressional recess Aug. 4.
   Wiseman said she told Pierce she could not fund the project over
the objections of career HUD employees who had been ``violently
opposed'' to the project.
   The project was eventually approved by Wiseman's successor, Janet
Hale, who said she believed she was ``acting on the approval of my
boss.''
   Wiseman also testified that DRG Funding Corp., a private lender
that was suspended from participating in a $5 billion program in
which HUD insured large portions of mortgages, was allowed to get
back into the program after lobbying from Hills, a former HUD
Secretary.
   DRG is now under FBI criminal investigation.
   Wiseman said DRG's ability to underwrite mortgages had been
placed on hold during the Reagan administration because of
infractions of department rules. The suspension remained despite a
meeting with Hills in late 1984 or early 1985 to get the
restrictions lifted.
   ``It was not a convincing argument,'' Wiseman said.
   But DRG's probation was lifted despite the concerns of staff
members, she said. ``It was later brought to my attention that Hills
had ... taken the case to Secretary Pierce. I was informed by staff
that there was a meeting,'' she said.
   Lawmakers expressed concern about the conflicting testimony
regarding Pierce.
   ``The factual noose seems to be tightening around Samuel Pierce's
neck,'' said Rep. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y.
   ``We were very careful about asking him if he had ever tried to
influence any project and we have two people making it very clear
that he wanted a particular project funded,'' said Rep. Christopher
Shays, R-Conn.
   Meanwhile, HUD filed suit in Forth Worth, Texas, on Friday
seeking to recover more than $2.5 million a Texas woman is accused
of bilking from the agency and spending on real estate, cars and
guns. The woman is one of 10 closing agents nationwide the agency
believes defrauded HUD of about $10 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
