<FIRST>r a PM-Names     07-15 0945</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Names,0983</SECOND>
<HEAD>Names in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Charles Scribner's Sons has contracted former
Secretary of State George P. Shultz to write two books, one on the
art of diplomacy and the other a memoir of his 6{ years as secretary
of state.
   Under the agreement announced Friday, Scribner's, part of
Macmillan Inc., has been granted world rights to both books.
   The statecraft book is related to a PBS series that MacNeil
Lehrer Productions is producing.
   Shultz served as secretary of state under President Reagan from
July 1982 until January. He currently is the Jack Steel Parker
professor of international economics at the Stanford Graduate School
of Business and honorary fellow at the Hoover Institution on War,
Revolution and Peace.
   His publications include ``Economy Policy Beyond the Headlines,''
1978; ``Workers and Wages in the Urban Labor Market,'' 1970, and
``Guidelines, Informal Controls and the Market Place,'' 1966.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York Gov. Mario Cuomo, who knows how to
keep people guessing about his possible presidential ambitions,
continues to talk about his lack of interest in discussing the
subject.
   As usual, he refused even to hint at a yes or no.
   ``I want to talk about it because I want to dispose of it,''
Cuomo was quoted as saying in Friday's edition of the Times Union.
   ``If I speak on the subject at all, it becomes an occasion for
speculation,'' Cuomo said. ``And so, for the time being, if anyone
does ask me about it, I'm simply not going to discuss it.''
   Cuomo then went on to talk about ``a thousand letters'' he's
received from people urging him to run for president _ ``letters
from some names that would shock you ... Republicans, people of
great stature in this country.''
   On Monday, Cuomo set off the latest round of speculation about
him and the presidency when he told a meeting of the New York State
Broadcasters Association that as a public servant he was
``obligated'' to think about running for president.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HOOSICK FALLS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grandma Moses, in the guise of actress
Cloris Leachman, has come home to the valley that inspired her
artist's eye.
   The town about 45 miles northeast of Albany gave a warm welcome
Friday to the actress who portrays Moses in the stage show ``Grandma
Moses _ An American Primitive.''
   ``I really believe we've found the heart and soul of what we're
trying to do here,'' Leachman, 63, told an audience of about 150
people, including about 15 descendants of Moses.
   Leachman sat with Dorothy Moses, 90, widow of Grandma Moses'
youngest son, Hugh; Jean Moses Harrington, 65; and Margery Moses
Fitzgerald, 60, both granddaughters of the painter.
   Anna Mary Robertson Moses was born in Eagle Bridge, just a few
miles from Hoosick Falls, moved to Virginia's Shenandoah Valley with
her husband, and returned at the age of 45.
   Moses began painting in her 70s, after her hands had grown too
weak for other tasks. She painted for three decades, illustrating
Clement Moore's ``'Twas the Night Before Christmas'' at the age of
100.
   Grandma Moses was 101 when she died in December 1961.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PATERSON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastside High School will be leaning on
someone new come September, following the city Board of Education's
replacement of disciplinarian Joe Clark as school principal.
   The school board Thursday unanimously approved Charles Lighty for
the high-profile job. In chosing Lighty, an elementary school
principal, board members said it was time to emphasize academics at
a school that became famous for Clark's barking, authoritarian style.
   Clark, 52, who is on a leave of absence at his South Orange home
recuperating from open heart surgery, already had announced his
intention not to return to Eastside in September.
   His no-nonsense approach to education was symbolized by a
baseball bat and bullhorn he wielded during patrols of the halls at
Eastside. His efforts were depicted in the movie ``Lean on Me.''
   Telephone calls to Lighty's home were not answered Friday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Saxophonist Stan Getz, pianist
Herbie Hancock, an 8-year-old vocalist and a man billed as the
world's first bagpipe jazz artist are among the players at this
year's North Sea Jazz Festival.
   Also scheduled to appear in the three-day festival, which opened
Friday, are the inveterate percussionist and band leader Art Blakey,
pianist Oscar Peterson and trumpeters Dizzy Gillespie and Miles
Davis.
   Organizers say they are expecting up to 50,000 visitors to watch
the more than 150 bands and dozens of soloists appearing at the
sprawling Congresgebouw complex here.
   Blakey is one of the three winners of this year's Bird Award, an
international jazz prize awarded at the festival and named after the
innovative alto saxophonist Charlie ``Bird'' Parker.
   Other winners of the trophy were Dutch pianist Misha Mengelberg
and British saxophonist John Surman.
   A novelty at this year's festival will be a daylong family
program dubbed ``Gigs for Kids,'' which includes bagpipe artist
Rufus Harley and 8-year-old skat singer Emily Haddad of Chicago,
billed as a ``miniature Ella Fitzgerald.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There's a new and younger Judge Wapner
on the bench.
   Frederick Wapner, 39, of Los Angeles, the son of the ``People's
Court'' jurist, was named Friday to the Los Angeles County Municipal
Court.
   He was one of five people, all current or former deputy district
attorneys, chosen by Gov. George Deukmejian. Wapner is the son of
Joseph Wapner, the judge of the nationally syndicated television
show, the governor's office said.
   The younger Wapner, a deputy district attorney since 1975,
replaces Stephen O'Neil, who was promoted to the Superior Court. The
salary for a Municipal Court judge is $82,052.
</TEXT>
