<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-89 0226EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-BlackCatholics     07-15 0491</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Black Catholics,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Archbishop Calls for Blacks to Lead Church ``From Within''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNE RUMSEY</BYLINE>
<UNK>Associated Press Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leader of the nation's 300 Roman Catholic
bishops admits there are persistent ``elements of racism'' in the
church, but is calling for a black priest's breakaway congregation
to return for the sake of unity.
   Archbishop John May of St. Louis, president of the National
Conference of Catholic Bishops, promised the Rev. George A.
Stallings Jr. the nation's two million black Catholics would be
given ``full voice'' in the church.
   ``It is possible to ... be a voice of conscience for the family
and lead that family from within,'' May said in a statement Friday.
   Stallings, 41, has been suspended for holding services the past
two weeks at his Imani Temple in defiance of Washington Cardinal
James Hickey.
   A spokesman for Stallings said he would have no comment on May's
statement or another call for unity from the nation's 13 black
bishops earlier this week.
   Stallings has said he formed the new congregation because the
Catholic Church has not addressed black concerns and he has charged
the church with racism.
   May's statement conceded, ``Surely, as all the bishops in this
country have acknowledged in the past, there have been elements of
racism in the church and there continue to be.
   ``We need to recognize more black leadership; our liturgies need
more of the vibrancy, and our policies more of the insight, of
African Americans,'' May said.
   He said the nation's 52 million Roman Catholics ``share the
sadness'' reflected in the black bishops' call Wednesday for
reconciliation.
   The black bishops' statement said in part, ``We sincerely hope
(Stallings' followers) are not commingling personal disappointment,
individually felt frustrations, and personal anger under the banner
of racism. Racism is a sin which the church must address. It is too
serious an issue to be used as a cover for selfish concerns.''
   Several priests have supported Stallings, however, including 15
who met with him in Chicago Thursday. They called for Hickey to lift
Stallings' suspension, imposed after the first service of the
renegade church at Howard University on July 2.
   Appearing Friday on The Oprah Winfrey Show, Stallings denied he
is forming the church for personal gain. ``I know exactly the
picture they're trying to paint ... but Martin Luther King Jr.,
Malcolm X, Jesse Jackson, people say they all have inflated egos,''
Stallings said on the national television program.
   He affirmed his plans to continue services despite the
suspension, and said he ``cannot be excommunicated from Jesus
Christ.''
   Stallings said Hickey should ``eat crow,'' and ``admit he's
wrong.''
   ``Since the Roman Catholic Church cannot make inroads into the
black community, all we are saying is, let us show you how. What's
wrong with that?'' he asked.
   Suspension means Stallings is not sanctioned to say Mass or
perform other sacraments. It is the strongest step Hickey can take
without moving to excommunicate Stallings.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890715-0010 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-89 0230EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-WanderingPlane-Probes     07-15 0669</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wandering Plane-Probes,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dramatic Rescue Prompts More Investigations of Pilot</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Wandering Plane Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials are investigating the pilot who
survived an 800-mile flight, bullet wound and crash-landing in the
ocean, expanding probes that began when three dozen guns and a can
of ether were found in Thomas Root's private plane.
   The reports that the Washington communications lawyer is under
investigation by several agencies added a peculiar twist to the tale
of Root's rescue from the Atlantic Ocean after apparently crashing
unconscious into the water.
   Officials at agencies said Root is being investigated by the U.S.
Customs Service over the weapons and ether, the North Carolina
Secretary of State's Office concerning possible securities
violations, the National Transportation Safety Board and the FBI,
which investigates crimes aboard aircraft.
   Widespread publicity over Root's unlikely survival prompted
Customs to expand its investigation Friday into Miami and North
Carolina.
   ``This is weird to say the least,'' said a Customs official, who
spoke on condition of anonymity.
   In addition, a review of documents at the Federal Communications
Commission showed Root repeatedly failed to comply with deadlines
and other requirements in cases before the commission.
   Root also represented numerous clients of a Georgia-based company
that another broadcast firm labeled a ``notorious application mill''
for FM broadcast licenses that allegedly has bilked hundreds of
individuals of their investments.
   The 35 guns, many loaded, were found during a search April 24 by
federal and local officials of Root's Cessna 210 at the Manassas,
Va., airport, said the Customs official.
   All the guns were legal under federal law, and all but one _ a
machine gun Root had registered with the federal Bureau of Alcohol,
Tobacco and Firearms but not with Virginia authorities _ were legal
under state law. The state has filed a misdemeanor charge against
him over the machine gun, the official said.
   Among the guns, including assault-style weapons and three
.357-caliber Magnums, the officials found silencers, ammunition
clips, handcuffs, an electrical stun gun and a five-gallon can of
ether _ which is used in cocaine production _ in the plane, the
Customs official said.
   During a May 31 interview with Root by Prince William County
Polie and a Customs agent, ``by and large he was able to account for
legal possession of those weapons.''
   ``Basically, he indicated that he was a gun collector,'' the
official said. But Root did not explain why he kept the weapons on
his plane _ registered to a Washington-based company he owns _ nor
why they were loaded.
   Root told officials the ether ``was used to clean his aircraft.
But of course that's not what you use to clean an aircraft with
unless you're going to blow it up,'' the official said.
   Customs kept the case open ``because when you come across this
many weapons ... we always continue to take a look to make sure no
Customs laws have been violated,'' he said.
   The search had been prompted by an unidentified source who said
``there was a suspicious aircraft at Manassas Airfield,'' the
Customs official said.
   Hollywood, Fla., Police Chief Richard Witt revealed Friday that
Root had been shot. The bullet traveled through his left rib cage
and his colon, left his body, and then pierced his arm. A powder
burn indicated Root was shot at close range, the chief said.
   In North Carolina, Secretary of State Rufus Edmisten said his
office had spoken with Root about a securities investigation
involving Georgia-based Sonrise Management Services and that the
lawyer ``knew he was under investigation.''
   Sonrise said in a statement that the only connection between the
company and Root ``is that he represents certain entities which also
number among our clientele.''
   Edmisten said Root was the attorney for investment partnerships
formed by Sonrise to obtain FCC licenses.
   Meanwhile, National Transportation Safety Board spokeswoman
Rachel Halterman said investigators ``have not come to any
conclusions and have not ruled out anything at all'' about what
caused the events on the plane Thursday.
</TEXT>
