<SECOND>PM-Cooke-Cable,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cooke Sells Cable TV Systems for $1.6 Billion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jack Kent Cooke, the owner of the Washington
Redskins, sold his cable television systems to six companies for
about $1.6 billion, according to a report published today.
   The business deal, believed to involve one of the three largest
purchase prices in cable history, is expected to net Cooke more than
$500 million in profit in two years, The Washington Post reported.
   The properties have 675,000 subscribers in 17 states and will be
sold to a consortium of companies that includes Tele-Communications
Inc., the Denver-based operator of the nation's largest group of
cable-television systems, and Inter-media Partners, a privately held
San Francisco company partly owned by Tele-Communications, said the
Post.
   Cooke paid a total of $1.05 billion for the systems in two deals
in 1987, investing about $200 million of his own money and borrowing
the rest, according to the newspaper.
   Other buyers include TCA Cable TV Inc. of Tyler, Texas; Chambers
Communications Corp. of Eugene, Ore., Falcon Cable TV of Los
Angeles; and a group including members of the John J. Rigas family,
which controls Adelphia Communications of Pennsylvania.
