<FIRST>r w PM-StarWars-Experiment     07-15 0313</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Star Wars-Experiment,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Star Wars' Particle Beam Fired Into Space</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon is studying results of a ``Star
Wars'' test that is considered a key step in U.S. research to deploy
futuristic weapons that could shoot powerful beams at enemy missiles.
   Defense Department officials on Friday confirmed completion of
the test, which involved firing a beam of electrically neutral
atomic particles into space for the first time.
   The BEAR test _ which stands for the Beam Experiment Aboard
Rocket _ is designed to test how an accelerator of neutral particles
would work in space.
   The experiment, which has been planned for more than a year, was
completed early Thursday morning at the White Sands Missile Range in
New Mexico, said Army Maj. William O'Connell, a spokesman for the
Strategic Defense Initiative Organization.
   Program scientists need to test whether neutral particle beams _
in this case, hydrogen atoms _ can be used to discriminate between
real and mock Soviet warheads.
   The spokesman said it was ``presumptive'' to announce whether the
test had been a success, since officials and scientists still need
to study the results of the experiment over the weekend before
releasing more information Monday.
   The experiment involved lifting into space _ just for a few
minutes _ a neutral particle beam accelerator atop a small Aires
rocket. Before the rocket returned to earth, the accelerator was to
be turned on for collection of data on how it worked and how the
beam moved.
   In June, a similar test was aborted when the rocket failed to
ignite on command.
   The Star Wars program is a research effort aimed at developing
lasers, beam accelerators and other futuristic weapons that could be
used to automatically shoot down nuclear missiles fired at the
United States or its allies. The Pentagon and Energy Department are
spending $4 billion on such research this year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
