<FIRST>r i PM-Romania-Rights     07-15 0198</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Romania-Rights,0202</SECOND>
<HEAD>Romania Bars U.N. Human Rights Investigator</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERN, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.N.-appointed special investigator on
human rights in Romania said that Bucharest has refused his request
for an entry visa.
   Joseph Voyame, a Swiss jurist named investigator for Romania last
March by the U.N. Human Rights Commission, said Romania's communist
authorities told him Friday that they consider the probe
``worthless.''
   Romania has come under international fire for the treatment of
its Hungarian minority and plans by President Nicolae Ceausescu _
apparently shelved now _ to raze thousands of villages in a ``rural
consolidation'' program.
   Romania, the first communist country subjected to special
scrutiny by the Human Rights Commission, is not alone in barring its
envoys. Iran refuses them entry, as did Afghanistan for years.
Israel has denied U.N.-mandated human rights investigators access to
the occupied Arab territories.
   Voyame told reporters he plans to travel to Hungary to interview
Romanian refugees there and expects to submit his report by December
as scheduled. The Human Rights Commission is due to debate the
report at its annual meeting next February.
   Voyame said he has gathered information so far from private human
rights groups and Romanian refugees in Switzerland.
</TEXT>
