<FIRST>r i PM-Korea     07-15 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Korea,0360</SECOND>
<HEAD>South Korea Calls Off Sports Talks With North Korea</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government accused communist North
Korea today of trying to stir unrest in South Korea and called off
talks on fielding a joint team at the 1990 Asian Games in China.
   In a letter to North Korea, South Korea canceled talks planned
for Tuesday at the border truce village of Panmunjom.
   The letter accused North Korea of slander and ``hostile political
maneuvering'' aimed at causing civil unrest in South Korea, but said
South Korea hoped talks would be resumed soon.
   The cancellation reflected the souring relations between the
countries over a series of illegal visits by South Koreans to the
north.
   Trips to North Korea without prior government approval are a
crime in South Korea. The government maintains that all contacts and
dialogue with the North must be made through official channels.
   The last sports meeting, the second in a series, was held in
March, but North Korea had refused to resume the talks until
recently.
   The two Koreas have tried to improve relations through a series
of talks that began in 1988, although little progress has been made,
with each side insisting on its own initiatives.
   Contacts grew chillier earlier this year when North Korea
demanded that South Korea cancel annual military exercises with the
United States
   Seoul since postponed other talks, including those on a
long-planned meeting between lawmakers from both nations, and
accused North Korea of encouraging secret visits by South Koreans to
stir up problems in the South.
   Moon Ik-hwan, a Presbyterian minister who made an unauthorized
visit to North Korea in March to see North Korean leader Kim Il
Sung, has been jailed on charges of violating national security laws.
   A student defied the Seoul government and attended an
international youth festival, which ended last weekend in Pyongyang,
triggering crackdowns on radical students in South Korea.
   An opposition lawmaker was arrrested June 28 for making a secret
trip to North Korea in August. Nine other people have been jailed
for failing to report the lawmaker to authorities.
</TEXT>
