<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-89 0520EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Somalia-Unrest     07-15 0445</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Somalia-Unrest,0458</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Says 10 Killed, 32 Injured in Mogadishu Clash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The capital of Somalia was reported calm
today, one day after state radio said 10 people were killed and 32
injured when security forces opened fire on locals who attacked them
with stones, knives and sticks.
   The clash broke out Friday near a mosque in a neighborhood of
western Mogadishu, according to Somali state radio.
   The casualties included ``troublemakers'' and members of the
security forces, according to a state radio broadcast monitored in
Nairobi, Somalia's western neighbor.
   A resident contacted by telephone Friday said it appeared troops
had opened fire as Moslem worshipers left their place of prayer.
Islam is the state religion in the impoverished East African nation
of about 9 million.
   The resident, who spoke on condition he not be identified
further, said gunfire erupted around midday in the capital on the
shores of the Indian Ocean and continued sporadically through the
afternoon.
   Residents contacted by telex from Nairobi said life in Mogadishu
appeared to have returned to normal today and that a 6 p.m. to 6
a.m. curfew imposed Friday was lifted.
   A statement by the Somali Interior Ministry, broadcast over state
radio late Friday, said a group of ``troublemakers hiding behind the
banner of religion'' caused the disturbances.
   Security forces tried to contain the situation peacefully, but
opened fire after the ``troublemakers'' attacked them with stones,
knives and sticks, according to the government statement.
   Ten people were killed and 32 wounded in the clash with
casualties on both sides of the violence, said the statement.
   Friday is normally the Moslem Sabbath but July 14 also was the
occasion for feast and celebration of the hajj, the Moslem
faithfuls' pilgrimage to the holy city of Mecca.
   There were reports during the week that several Moslem religious
leaders had been picked up by the authorities, but it was not known
whether the alleged detentions had anything to do with Friday's
violence. Further information on the reported arrests was not
available.
   Last Sunday, an unidentified gunman shot to death Mogadishu's
Roman Catholic Bishop Salvatore Pietro Colombo. It also was not
known whether the disturbances were connected to that incident.
There are an estimated 2,000 Roman Catholics in Somalia.
   Somalia, on the horn of East Africa that juts into the Indian
Ocean, has been led since 1969 by the autocratic President Mohamed
Siad Barre as a one-party state.
   Since 1981, Somalia has battled the Somali National Movement, a
northern insurgency that demands Barre's removal. Intensified
fighting between the insurgents and the government over the last 18
months has driven more than 200,000 Somalis into refugee camps in
neighboring Ethiopia.
</TEXT>
