<FIRST>r a PM-TeenQueen     07-15 0374</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Teen Queen,0384</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Delays Spurned Beauty Queen's Try to Enter National Contest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA MYERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has agreed to hear the case of
a teen-age Nevada beauty queen who has filed a lawsuit to enter a
national pageant under way in California.
   Heather Anne McLeod sued the operators of the Miss Teen USA
pageant in San Bernardino, Calif., after she was disqualified for
allegedly breaking the rules by competing in both Nevada and
California Miss Teen contests the same year.
   U.S. District Judge Roger Foley said Friday he would review Ms.
McLeod's case Tuesday, one day before preliminary competition begins
in the national Miss Teen USA contest, with $150,000 in prizes for
the winner.
   Karen Gee, a spokeswoman for the national pageant, wouldn't say
whether it's too late for Ms. McLeod to join the contest if a judge
rules in her favor. Taping began Friday for the swimsuit competition
portion of the test. The show's finale is July 25.
   Ms. McLeod's attorney said the 18-year-old wants $200,000 in
damages if she is barred from the contest, to make up for the
``extreme mental anxiety, public humiliation, personal
embarrassment, public ridicule, and loss of reputation'' she will
suffer.
   The attorney, Charles Zeh, unsuccessfully sought a temporary
restraining order Thursday ``in hopes of getting a hearing and an
order as quickly as possible to get her into the contest.''
   ``Heather is here waiting ... time is of the essence,'' he said.
   The University of Nevada-Reno psychology student, who attended
high school in San Diego, was disqualifed from the national contest
June 30 after winning the Nevada pageant June 22 in Las Vegas. She
earlier had taken part in the California state contest.
   Zeh contends Ms. McLeod wasn't told she could be disqualified for
competing in both California and Nevada pageants and wasn't given a
copy of the rules.
   Stacey Bentley, 18, who finished second in the Miss Nevada Teen
contest, has taken Ms. McLeod's place in preliminary activities of
the Miss Teen USA competition.
   As far as the Miss Teen USA officials are concerned, Ms. Gee
said, ``Heather McLeod is not the Miss Nevada Teen delegate; the
Miss Nevada Teen delegate is down here competing.''
</TEXT>
