<FIRST>u i PM-Soviet-Strikes     07-15 0569</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Strikes,0587</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Officials Report Losses from Spreading Coal Strikes</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Osiniki correct spelling</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Spreading strikes in the Kuzbass coal region of
Siberia are causing heavy economic losses, newspapers reported today
as officials appealed to miners in at least nine cities to return to
work.
   Settlements were reported with miners in two cities,
Mezhdurechinsk and Osiniki, but strikes elsewhere have spread, the
reports said.
   Soviet newspapers described a chaotic situation in the Kuzbass,
an important coal-producing region about 1,600 miles east of Moscow.
It supplies fuel to the metallurgical industries in the Ural
Mountains to the west.
   Thousands of miners and their families were said to be meeting in
town squares throughout the coal-producing basin to protest harsh
living and working conditions.
   Authorities reported an end to the strike Thursday, but miners
expanded their demands from economic issues, such as food, housing
and health care, to broader demands for political change, Soviet
reports said.
   The crisis was sharpest in the town of Prokopevsk, where
production was virtually halted, the Communist Party newspaper
Sotsialisticheskaya Industriya reported in a dispatch from Kemerov
Oblast in the Kuzbass.
   ``Events in the Kuzbass have taken a sharp turn,'' the newspaper
reported. Although miners returned to work in Mezhdurechensk, in
other mining towns in the basin ``the situation has sharply
intensified.''
   Mining Minister Mikhail I. Shchadov was in the area, rushing from
mine to mine, ``spending many hours speaking to the strikers'' and
trying to end the stoppage, the newspaper said.
   In addition to the agreement reached in Mezhdurechensk, where the
strike began Tuesday, authorities also reached a settlement with
miners in Osiniki, according to Sotsialisticheskaya Industriya and
Pravda, another party newspaper.
   Strikes continued at Prokopevsk; at Kisilevsk, five out of 10
mines were on strike; two mines were on strike at Lenin-Kuznets; in
Kemerov, the administrative center of the region, the Severnaya and
Butovkskaya mines were on strike; miners were striking in
Novokuznetsk, according to the newspaper reports.
   Miners in Byelov and Anzhero-Sudzhesk continued to work, but
still made demands on authorities, the reports said. Reports said
miners in nine cities were striking, although the published lists
did not match.
   The reports said that despite a rather chaotic situation, rife
with rumors, miners' strike committees that formed Friday were
keeping social order.
   ``At their demand, sales of liquor were stopped and narcotics
control points were established along highways,'' Pravda reported in
a dispatch from its correspondent at the scene.
   It said that on Thursday in Novokuznetsk and on Friday in
Kemerov, ``efforts were made by the so-called `Democratic Union' and
several other informal organizations to spread anti-Soviet slogans,
but they received a resolute rebuff.''
   Authorities throughout the region tried to talk the miners back
to work.
   ``Democracy means not only rights, but also responsbility,
discipline and organization,'' Sotsialisticheskaya Industriya warned.
   Strikes were once hushed up and brutally suppressed in the Soviet
Union, where they were considered a Western phenomenon resulting
from capitalist exploitation. This year, however, coal strikes have
generally ended after several days with government concessions.
   Last March, more than 100 coal miners in the Ural city of Vorkuta
struck to protest increased work orders. In April, miners stayed
underground in the Siberian city of Norilsk to demand a 30 percent
wage increase.
   Twenty-four miners are reported to be staying underground in
Alexandria in the Ukraine with demands similar to their Kuzbass
counterparts.
</TEXT>
