<FIRST>r a PM-SoybeanCorner     07-15 0618</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soybean Corner,0634</SECOND>
<HEAD>CFTC Will Investigate CBOT Actions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Commodities Futures Trading Commission says it
will review the trading positions of Chicago Board of Trade
directors to see if any of them profited from the drop in soybean
prices precipitated by their emergency order earlier this week.
   The CFTC made the announcement Friday as Italian agribusiness
giant Ferruzzi said it would renew its court battle to recover
losses from a Board of Trade order forcing soybean traders to
liquidate large positions in the market.
   Raul Gardini, chairman of Ferruzzi Finanzaria SpA, reiterated in
Milan that his company's accumulation of futures contracts to take
delivery of 23 million bushels of soybeans was legal.
   A Feruzzi spokesman said a lawsuit probably would be filed in
Chicago, but did not provide a timetable. The company also indicated
it might seek compensation for unrealized profits as well as damage
to its reputation.
   On Thursday, U.S. District Judge James Zaghel denied a request by
two of the company's subsidiaries _ Ferruzzi Trading International
SA and Ferruzzi USA Inc. _ for a restraining order and a permanent
injunction ending the directive issued Tuesday by the CBOT.
   Zagel told CBOT attorneys to file a motion to dismiss the lawsuit
by Tuesday, with a response due July 24.
   Gardini didn't specify the amount of losses Ferruzzi suffered as
a result of the board's order, which required all traders to reduce
their July contract soybean holdings to 1 million bushels by the
close of trading Thursday.
   CBOT directors have said they issued the liquidation order
because the open July soybean contracts totaled about 40 million
bushels and there were abnormally low levels of stocks available to
satisfy the contracts _ a situation that would have resulted in a
number of defaults without the exchange's intervention.
   Any player with a large enough share of the market _ a position
referred to as ``cornering the market'' _ theoretically could force
those on the other end of its futures contracts to deliver, possibly
causing a scramble for supplies that would drive the price of its
soybeans up sharply.
   Soybean prices for July delivery rose 6 cents to $7.03{ a bushel
on Friday. Despite the gain, the price was still well below $7.26 a
bushel, the level at which July soybeans settled on Tuesday before
the Board of Trade's directive.
   ``Ferruzzi and all major world traders are convinced that the
board made a mistake and has to suffer the consequences,'' Gardini
said about the potential lawsuit.
   Ferruzzi has said it accumulated large soybean supplies to keep
its processing plants running and to meet export commitments, and
also that its large futures market position was a hedge against
price fluctuations.
   In Washington, the CFTC said it would review the trading
positions of exchange directors and the minutes of the meeting at
which the decision was made to force liquidation of soybean
contracts.
   Board of Trade Chairman Karsten Mahlmann has said that none of
those involved in the decision held a position in the soybean market
when they voted to issue the emergency order.
   Meanwhile, Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., chairman of the Senate
Agriculture Committee, expressed concern over the actions taken by
the Board of Trade.
   ``There have been serious allegations that there may have been an
effort to manipulate the soybean futures market,'' he said ``I will
insist on a full and rigorous investigation of any wrongdoing and
that the perpetrators be punished to full extent of the law.
   ``If reforms are necessary to prevent these types of
manipulations, I will insist on making them when this issue comes
before my committee later this year.''
   The Agriculture Committee oversees the CFTC, which is up for
reauthorization this year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
