<FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     07-15 0582</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms in Plains, Northwest; Cool in East</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Strong thunderstorms stretched from New Mexico to the central
Plains and whipped parts of Oregon and Idaho, while cool Canadian
air chilled many parts of the East.
   Thunderstorm winds gusted to 60 mph and toppled trees at
Lovington, N.M., on Friday, an airplane was flipped over at an
airport near Hobbs and power lines were downed in and around
Portales.
   Winds also tore the roof off a building at Logan and boats and
boathouses were damaged at Ute Lake. Hail the size of dimes covered
the ground and halted traffic on Interstate 40 west of Santa Rosa.
   In northern Kansas, high winds downed trees and damaged grain
bins at Logan. Streets flooded in Stockton, where three inches of
rain fell within an hour, and flooding also occurred along the south
fork of the Solomon River.
   Three inches of rain also fell in an hour at Trumball, Neb., and
heavy rains washed out roads near Cairo and caused nearby Dry Creek
to overflow its banks.
   Thunderstorm winds also buffeted eastern Oregon and northern
Idaho. Winds gusted to 64 mph at Baker, Ore., and blew down trees
near Marsing and Homedale, Idaho.
   Thunderstorm rains deluged extreme southern Louisiana, flooding
streets in downtown Lake Charles.
   Other thunderstorms were over southern Oklahoma, north-central
Texas, and along a stationary front from central Mississippi to the
South Carolina coast.
   High pressure over Lake Superior brought cool air to the upper
Great Lakes, the central Appalachians and northern New England,
where overnight temperatures were in the 40s and 50s. Marquette,
Mich., tied its record low for the date late Friday with a reading
of 43 degrees.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms from the
coast of the Carolinas into Florida, and from the eastern and
central Gulf Coast across the lower and middle Mississippi Valley to
the Plains from eastern Texas to South Dakota. Scattered showers and
thunderstorms were forecast for the northern Rockies and sunny skies
were expected elsewhere.
   Highs were expected to be in the 60s and 70s along the Pacific
Coast; the 70s from portions of the central Plains and South Dakota
across much of the upper and middle Mississippi Valley, the Great
Lakes and northern Ohio Valley to New England; the 90s across the
Florida Peninsula, and from parts of the lower Mississippi Valley
across Texas and the southern Rockies to much of Arizona, New
Mexico, Nevada, Utah and Idaho; and above 100 degrees across the
Desert Southwest and inland valleys of Southern California. The
remainder of the nation was expected to have highs in the 80s.
   Temperatures at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 36 degrees at Marquette,
Mich., to 98 degrees at Phoenix.
   Other reports:
   _ East: Atlanta 75 cloudy; Boston 64 fair; Buffalo 55 fair;
Charleston, S.C. 76 cloudy; Cincinnati 64 fair; Cleveland 58 fair;
Detroit 57 fair; Miami 78 fair; New York 67 fair; Philadelphia 63
fair; Pittsburgh 58 fair; Portland, Maine 60 fair; Washington 68
fair.
   _ Central: Bismarck 53 fair; Chicago 67 partly cloudy;
Dallas-Fort Worth 74 thunderstorms; Denver 62 fair; Des Moines 68
showery; Indianapolis 64 cloudy; Kansas City 68 thunderstorms;
Minneapolis-St. Paul 66 partly cloudy; Nashville 68 fair; New
Orleans 77 cloudy; St. Louis 70 fair.
   _ West: Albuquerque 72 windy; Anchorage 59 cloudy; Las Vegas 90
fair; Los Angeles 66 fair; Phoenix 96 partly cloudy; Salt Lake City
68 fair; San Diego 67 cloudy; San Francisco 57 cloudy; Seattle 59
cloudy.
</TEXT>
