<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-89 0600EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-GreenRiver     07-15 0643</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Green River,0664</SECOND>
<HEAD>Relative Hopes Green River Suspect is Killer; Police Sort Through
Belongings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARRIE FIGDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seven years after his sister's body was found
along the Green River, one of the first victims in the nation's
worst serial murder case, Garrett Mills says he can only hope police
have the killer.
   Police began sorting through the 1,800 videotapes and 55 cartons
and bags of materials seized from William Jay Stevens II, a former
law student named in court papers as a ``viable suspect'' in the
slayings. The sorting could take a month.
   Stevens has not been charged in the case and he denies any
involvement. His name became public late this week in an affidavit
supporting a search warrant for two Spokane homes used by him.
   The affidavit said he was under investigation in the case and
might be linked to at least 17 other homicide victims whose bodies
were found along highways between Portland and Vancouver, British
Columbia, and between Seattle and Spokane.
   Mills' sister, 16-year-old Opal Charmaine Mills was one of the 40
known Green River victims. Police have blamed the killer for the
disappearance of eight other young women.
   Ranging in age from 15 to 36, the female victims vanished between
July 1982 and early 1984. Of the 40 corpses, 36 were found in the
Seattle area and four near Portland, Ore. Four remain unidentified.
   The case takes its name from the site south of Seattle where the
first five corpses were found in the summer of 1982.
   ``I paid attention a lot at first, but I got tired of getting my
hopes up,'' Mills, 25, said Friday of the investigation.
   He added, ``I hope it's him, but I don't know.''
   Stevens is serving a one-year term in the county jail in Seattle
for the burglary of a police equipment supply store in 1979 and
additional time for walking away from a work-release center in 1981.
   He was rearrested in Spokane on Jan. 10.
   Stevens was found after ``Manhunt,'' a nationally syndicated
television show, aired a program in December about the Green River
killings. One tipster directed investigators to Gonzaga University
Law School in Spokane, where Stevens had attended classes for 3{
years and was president of the student bar.
   ``Whether or not this person is simply the victim of a bizarre
set of circumstances or in fact responsible for some of the crimes
in King County, we don't know yet, and that's exactly what we're
trying to determine by going through the material we recovered with
the warrant,'' Green River Task Force Commander Robert C. Evans said
Friday.
   Stevens, who declined jailhouse interviews, ``is concerned he's
being singled out as the answer to a longtime investigation,'' said
his attorney, Craig Beles.
   ``He feels basically like anybody who is innocent of the offenses
being looked at by the Green River Task Force. He is angry and
frightened,'' said Beles. ``He's a colorful character, but he's no
murderer.''
   No personal items belonging to any Green River victims were found
in Wednesday's searches, Evans said.
   Evans acknowledged the King County Police task force had found
``no smoking gun,'' but he said an initial study of 405 documents
charting Stevens' movements between 1981 and 1989 showed they
sometimes closely paralleled the killings.
   Records seized when he was arrested show he traveled extensively
between Seattle, Portland, Spokane and Vancouver, British Columbia,
under at least four aliases during the period, Evans said.
   After his arrest, Spokane authorities found in searches that
Stevens possessed several police-type vehicles, 26 license plates,
29 firearms and about 100 police badges, investigators said.
   The task force has long suspected the killer could be a police
officer or someone posing as one, Evans said.
   In the affidavit, many who knew Stevens said he liked
pornography, frequented prostitutes and carried photographs of
mutilated women.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
