<FIRST>r a PM-Dukakis-TaxHike     07-15 0388</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dukakis-Tax Hike,0400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dukakis Responds to Budget Woes, Drop in State's Bond Rating</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARLENE LEVINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Michael S. Dukakis took more heat for his 1990
budget cuts, which critics say could have been avoided had he acted
swiftly to limit the state's financial troubles a year ago, during
his presidential campaign.
   Demonstrators on Friday poured inside the Statehouse and marched
to the doors of the governor's office chanting: ``No more cuts.''
Dukakis was not in, and they left peacefully about 20 minutes later.
   ``Let's send a message throughout the Commonwealth of
Massachusetts,'' Boston Mayor Raymond Flynn said at the
demonstration. ``We are going to restore some semblance of decency
and respect and compassion for people who need our help.''
   Meanwhile, lawmakers vowed to restore $100 million in state aid
to cities and towns that the governor vetoed to balance the fiscal
1990 budget.
   Dukakis returned to the Statehouse later Friday to face other bad
news: Standard &amp; Poor's dropped Massachusetts' bond rating for the
second time this year. The agency cited financial disarray in
Massachusetts government. The move will add millions to borrowing
costs.
   ``It's not unexpected. ... Had we demonstrated fiscal strength,
we wouldn't have had to do what we did yesterday,'' Dukakis said of
the budget cuts.
   Dukakis defended his 1990 budget cuts as an ``essential part of
getting the state back on track.''
   The governor has come under fire for not acting swiftly when the
state began to run into financial trouble a year ago.
   ``They've been whistling while Rome burned in this
administration,'' said Rep. John Flood, a Democrat who chairs the
House of Representatives Taxation committee.
   ``This is not a surprise to a lot of people,'' Flood said. ``It
was avoidable and the administration chose to ignore the warnings.''
   Dukakis aides also announced the governor was postponing signing
a bill legislators passed early Friday that would impose an income
tax surcharge to make up the 1989 budget deficit and pay outstanding
Medicaid debts. The measure is projected to raise $744 million over
18 months.
   ``He plans to sign it, assuming all the legal and technical
questions are answered,'' said aide Mindy Lubber.
   Citizens for Limited Taxation and other anti-tax advocates say
they'll take the income tax issue to the 1990 ballot to seek a
refund.
</TEXT>
