<FIRST>r a PM-PlaneCrash     07-15 0252</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Plane Crash,0259</SECOND>
<HEAD>Small Plane Crashes, Three Dead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROMEOVILLE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A single-engine plane smashed into a
machine shop shortly after takeoff, killing all three people aboard
and injuring two workers at the shop, authorities said.
   The Walco Tool and Engineering Co., which had about 50 employees
working at the time of the crash, is about a quarter mile from the
runway of Lewis University Airport.
   ``There was this gigantic explosion,'' said Joe Gladkowski, 40, a
machinist at the shop.
   One of the men, a machinist, was listed in serious condition at a
hospital with burns over more than half of his body. Another
employee was treated and released.
   Witnesses said the plane had trouble gaining altitude during
takeoff.
   ``It appeared on takeoff to be unstable and was moving at a low
rate toward its climb,'' said Federal Aviation Administration
spokesman Mort Edelstein. ``Suddenly it took a left turn, went down
behind trees, struck a building and exploded into flames.''
   The Walco building is in a small industrial park located near a
pastoral care center run by the Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Joliet.
   Gladkowski said some employees had just gotten up from eating
lunch at a counter where the passenger section of the plane landed
on the building. The plane struck a solid beam and did not cause
major damage to the building.
   ``It's a blessing more people were not injured,'' said Walco
president David Walsh. ``There could be over a million dollars of
machinery damaged, but that doesn't matter.''
</TEXT>
