<FIRST>r i PM-Lebanon     07-15 0464</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon,0478</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shiite Clashes, Syrian-Christian Duels Amid Power Blackout</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rival Shiite Moslem militias clashed in
the slums of south Beirut today and Syrian and Christian forces
fought artillery battles across the capital amid a power blackout
caused by fuel shortages.
   Police said one person was killed and four were wounded in the
four-hour clash between the mainstream Shiite Amal militia, which is
backed by Syria, and the pro-Iranian Hezbollah, or Party of God.
   The two factions have clashed intermittently since April 1988 as
they vied for dominance of 1.2 million Shiites, the largest single
sect in Lebanon.
   By police count, the new casualties brought the overall toll of
the power struggle to 561 killed and 1,554 wounded.
   Syrian troops deployed in west Beirut sent patrols at 4 a.m. into
the low-income suburbs to disengage the militiamen and enforce a
cease-fire between the secular Amal and the fundamentalist
Hezbollah, a police spokesman said.
   The spokesman, who cannot be named in line with regulations, said
Syrian gunners in west Beirut sporadically shelled the coast from
east Beirut to the port of Byblos, 28 miles to the north,
maintaining their sea blockade of the Christian heartland.
   He said artillery fire fell around Byblos and Jounieh, another
port about 12{ miles north of Beirut. No casualties were reported.
   Christian gunners of army commander Gen. Michel Aoun fired back
with 155mm guns, targeting positions along west Beirut's seaside
districts.
   The police spokesman said at least one round exploded ``within a
few yards'' of a Syrian artillery emplacement in a deserted soccer
field in the fashionable Manara district.
   ``We don't know if the Syrians suffered any casualties. They
usually evacuate their casualties to their own field hospitals and
clinics which are not under our jurisdiction,'' the police spokesman
said.
   Syria's army command does not comment on losses among its 40,000
soldiers, stationed in Lebanon under a 1976 Arab League peacekeeping
mandate.
   The blockade of the Christian enclave has caused fuel oil
shortages at Beirut's main power generating plant in suburban Zouk.
The sea blockade has prevented shipments from arriving from abroad,
and checkpoints around the enclave obstructed supplies from
refineries in south and north Lebanon.
   The electricity authority announced that as of today its
generators will supply only the main water pumping station in Beirut
and major hospitals and telecommunication switchboards with two
hours of power every 24 hours on rotating basis.
   The public in both sectors of the divided capital and in the
Christian heartland to the north will receive none.
   It was the second time that the city has plunged into total
darkness since the confrontation between Aoun and the Syrians began
March 8. Last month's crisis was resolved after a partial lift of
the land siege.
</TEXT>
