<FIRST>r i PM-Vatican-Executions     07-15 0184</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Vatican-Executions,0189</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vatican Happy Indiana Teen-ager Spared, Regrets Executions In Cuba</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Vatican is pleased that Indiana teen-ager
Paula Cooper was spared from the electric chair but regrets that
four Cuban military officers were executed, spokesman Joaquin
Navarro said today.
   Pope John Paul II had pleaded for clemency for Ms. Cooper, who
was sentenced to death for murdering an elderly Bible teacher when
she was 15, and for former Gen. Arnaldo Ochoa and three other former
Cuban officers convicted of drug trafficking.
   The Indiana Supreme Court Thursday commuted Ms. Cooper's sentence
to 60 years in prison. Also Thursday, Ochoa, a war hero who fought
with Fidel Castro in Cuba's revolution, and the three others were
executed by a firing squad.
   ``One is very happy to know that Paula Cooper received mercy,''
Navarro said in a statement released by the Vatican press office.
   ``On the other hand, one learned with regret the news of the
execution in Cuba of the four people for whom the Holy Father had
asked for a gesture of clemency for understandable humanitarian
reasons,'' he said.
</TEXT>
