<FIRST>r i PM-Philippines-Typhoon 1stLd-Writethru   07-15 0309</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Philippines-Typhoon, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0470,0318</SECOND>
<HEAD>Typhoon Roars Toward Philippines, U.S. Bases on Alert</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 3 grafs after 5th graf `Strong winds...' to UPDATE with
details on alert at Clark Air Base. Pickup 6th graf `Gordon is...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Typhoon Gordon, the strongest storm to
threaten the Philippines this year, gained strength today as it
roared toward Luzon, the country's main island, officials said.
   Storm warnings were raised over 10 provinces and at the six U.S.
military bases. The U.S. military's Far East Network described
Gordon as a ``super typhoon'' and said it would strike the northern
island of Luzon early Sunday.
   At 5 p.m., Gordon had peak winds of 128 mph and was heading
toward Luzon at 14 mph from a position 270 miles northeast of Manila.
   Earlier today, Gordon had top winds of 116 mph.
   Strong winds buffeted Manila late today, but there were no
reports of damage.
   At Clark Air Base, 50 miles north of Manila, officials canceled
all inspections, training and other activities. The U.S.-run base's
emergency rescue and clean-up units were placed on alert and
non-essential personnel were ordered home.
   The Far East Network said some Military Airlift Command flights
to and from Clark would also be canceled because of the typhoon.
Heavy rains were expected in the Clark area late today, officials
said.
   There are 40,000 U.S. troops, civilian employees and military
dependents stationed at the six installations.
   Gordon is expected to cut across the northern tip of Luzon before
it moves out to the South China Sea later Sunday, weather
forecasters said.
   Residents of coastal areas were warned to take ``extreme
precaution'' against high waves and flash floods.
   The Philippine Coast Guard ordered all sea-going vessels on Luzon
not to leave port.
   Philippine Airlines said it canceled one domestic flight and
expected to ground more planes as the typhoon neared.
</TEXT>
