<FIRST>r i PM-Afghanistan 1stLd-Writethru a0468 07-15 0303</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Afghanistan, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0468,0309</SECOND>
<HEAD>Car Bomb Kills Nine, Injures 49; Afghanistan Blames Guerrillas</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with nine dead, 49 injured, blast blamed
on guerrillas. ADDS byline.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DILIP GANGULY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A car bomb exploded near the center of
the capital today, killing at least nine people and injuring 49,
officials said.
   No one claimed responsibilty for the blast, but the government
blamed Moslem guerrillas and unidentified ``foreign agents'' who
support them.
   The guerrillas, based in neighboring Pakistan and supported
mainly by the United States and Saudi Arabia, have been fighting for
more than a decade to overthrow the Soviet-backed government.
   The bomb, hidden in a parked Toyota truck, exploded at noon on
Nader Shah Road near the city's center, shattering windows 300 yards
away and throwing bomb fragments 400 yards, police said.
   The blast left a crater six feet wide, six feet long and three
feet deep, officials said.
   Hospital sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said at
least 10 of the injured were in critical condition.
   ``I saw people on the road. There were people with their heads
totally smashed,'' said Mohammad Nabi Andar, who arrived at the
scene five minutes after the blast.
   The explosion prompted stepped up security in the city of 2.25
million people. Police and soldiers were manning checkpoints around
the city, and all vehicles were stopped and searched.
   ``The explosion is the work of our opponents and foreign agents
who support them,'' said Foreign Ministry spokesman Mohammad Nabi
Amani. ``It was a very nasty thing to do just after Eid.'' Because
of the Eid al-Adha, the three-day Moslem feast of sacrifice, the
casualties were probably fewer.
   ``Had it been a normal day, at least 100 or 200 people may have
died,'' said police officer Mohammad Naim.
</TEXT>
