<FIRST>u i PM-Honduras-Bombing 2ndLd-Writethru a0474 07-15 0409</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Honduras-Bombing, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0474,0417</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leftist Group Claims Responsibility for Attack on U.S. Servicemen</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to CORRECT that those injured were U.S. Army soldiers,
not members of North Dakota National Guard. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDDY CUEVAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leftist group has claimed
responsibility for the bombing that injured seven U.S. Army soldiers.
   ``Yankee soldiers are only safe in their own land because here
they are the target of our bullets and explosives,'' the Morazanista
Liberation Front said in a communique issued Friday.
   The front, thought to be an arm of the outlawed Communist Party
founded in 1979, has claimed responsibility for at least five other
attacks, including three this year. Twenty-two U.S. soldiers were
injured in those incidents.
   ``The Morazanista sword is raised to expel or eliminate gringo
invaders,'' said the communique, which was delivered to the
newspaper La Prensa in San Pedro Sula, 125 miles north of the
capital.
   Police said a homemade bomb was thrown Thursday night at a group
of nine U.S. Army military policemen in civilian clothes as they
passed by the Lido Discotheque in La Ceiba, a coastal town 200 miles
north of Tegucigalpa.
   The four most seriously injured were flown to a U.S. military
hospital in San Antonio, Texas, U.S. officials said. Three others
were being treated at Enrique Soto Cano air base near Tegucigalpa.
Two escaped injury.
   All nine soldiers were from 459th Military Police Company, based
at Fort Davis in Panama. They had come to Honduras on temporary duty
to take part in a series of U.S.-Honduran joint military exercises.
   The nine military policemen were on security-escort duty with a
North Dakota National Guard convoy that was returning from drills in
northern Honduras to the base at Soto Cano when it stopped near La
Ceiba for the night.
   Charles V. Barclay, U.S. Embassy spokesman, said Thursday the
nine military policemen went into town without leave.
   The front ``called on the North American people to exert pressure
on your Senate and Congress, pressure so that your young sons will
not die in foreign lands defending imperial causes.
   ``Our actions will continue claiming Yankee casualties in the
pursuit of the war of liberation we are waging against the
invader,'' the communique said. ``The national dignity cannot be
trampled with impunity.''
   The United States maintains a permanent force of at least 1,200
troops in Honduras but thousands more rotate through every year on
training missions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
