<DOCNO> AP890715-0053 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-89 1055EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Budget     07-15 0660</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Budget,660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Budget Crunch Pitting Small Programs Against Popular Ones</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Outside the closed meeting rooms of the House
Appropriations Committee last week, the view was the same: clusters
of men and women leaning against walls, talking, reading newspapers,
killing time.
   It was a vigil of lobbyists, waiting for members of the
Appropriations subcommittees to strike their deals and map in
private how the government would spend more than half of the $1.17
trillion federal budget for the 1990 fiscal year.
   For many of the lobbyists, the wait was grim. After years of
federal budget constraints, advocates for programs that could once
count on generous government treatment are finding Uncle Sam
stingier than he used to be. And they're competing with each other
for the same scarce federal dollars.
   ``The first clue is that attendance here is 10 percent of what it
usually is,'' said David Bradley, motioning down the Rayburn House
Office Building corridor, as he and other lobbyists waited outside a
meeting of the Appropriations labor, health and human services
subcommittee. ``That's because there's no money.''
   Bradley, lobbying for low-income programs, was exaggerating, but
only slightly.
   The labor subcommittee has jurisdiction over the government's
health, welfare and education programs, a $155 billion slice of the
federal pie for the coming fiscal year, which begins Oct. 1.
   But law requires that about two-thirds of that be spent on
specific programs. The rest of it is up for grabs, and small
programs with limited appeal to lawmakers are finding themselves
competing for funds with politically popular initiatives for
education, AIDS research, the homeless and the like.
   This strikes fear in the hearts of lobbyists for the government's
less visible programs.
   ``Poverty isn't popular,'' said Bradley. ``What we're seeing is
an understated but very definite realignment of government
priorities. We're seeing interest flow in three or four areas, and
an ending of the government role in other areas.''
   Outside another closed door, this one in the Capitol basement,
another group of lobbyists waited as the Appropriations treasury and
postal service subcommittee wrote its $18.5 billion bill.
   Some of them were working on behalf of postal subsidies for small
newspapers, charities, unions and schools, which are entitled to
lower mailing rates. The Reagan administration had tried to
terminate the $430 million program, and President Bush has proposed
limiting it.
   Advocates were hoping to win a slight increase for the subsidies,
but they acknowledged they faced formidable competition for federal
funds from another area within the subcommittee's jurisdiction.
   ``The big issue in this committee is drug enforcement,'' said
Carolyn Emigh, counsel for the Non-Profit Mailers Association.
   Anti-drug programs are among the most popular programs on Capitol
Hill these days, as lawmakers heed polls indicating that drugs are
the foremost problem on the minds of voters. Their appeal makes it
easy for members of Congress to lavish them with money.
   ``Right now drugs are pretty high on the list,'' Sen. Robert
Byrd, D-W.Va., chairman of the Senate Appropriations Committee,
acknowledged in an interview.
   Congressional spending priorities are easy to discern by studying
the way the Senate Appropriations Committee divided up the $658
billion it oversees among its 13 subcommittees.
   The three largest increases over 1989 spending levels were of
$5.3 billion to the subcommittee that oversees veterans, housing,
science and space programs; $4 billion to the panel that controls
health and education; and $1.8 billion to the subcommittee with
jurisdiction over law enforcement.
   That still left Byrd fielding complaints at a committee meeting
last week that several subcommittees had been granted too little
money.
   The tight money seems not to have stopped lawmakers themselves
from seeking funds for projects within their home districts, however.
   Byrd said the Appropriations interior subcommittee, which he also
chairs, has so far received 1,971 requests for money for projects.
And Sen. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa, chairman of the Appropriations labor,
health and human services panel, said he had gotten 455 requests.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
