<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--BuriedTreasure     07-15 0130</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Buried Treasure,0132</SECOND>
<HEAD>2,000-Year-Old Treasures Being Raised from Seabed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FLORENCE, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Divers have recovered treasures buried
underwater for more than 2,000 years in the wreck of a Roman ship,
newspapers reported Saturday.
   The expedition, which started nearly two weeks ago, has uncovered
a late 2nd century B.C. bronze Grecian oil-lamp in the shape of a
deer's head, a fragment of a small wooden statue, and various other
items hidden in the seabed around the ship, the reports said.
   The 65-foot-long ship, which sank in the Gulf of Baratti 12 miles
from the island of Elba, was discovered in 1974, and some of its
valuable objects were recovered by private treasure hunters.
   The government organized an expedition to bring up the remaining
items of archaelogical interest this summer.
</TEXT>
