<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-89 1103EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Mexico-Debt     07-15 0774</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Debt,0797</SECOND>
<HEAD>Debt Reduction Vital To Economic Recovery</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS ANGELO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mexico badly needs the help President Bush is
offering to reduce payments on its foreign debt, but even with
substantial relief, coaxing the country out of seven years of
stagnation may be a slow process.
   ``Mexican as well as foreign investors are waiting for the
starting flag that the solution to the debt negotiations will
give,'' said President Carlos Salinas de Gortari, who met with Bush
last week.
   Attention was focused last week on talks between Mexico and
creditor banks as world leaders gathered in Paris for an economic
summit. Bush wanted an agreement as a showpiece for its strategy to
reduce the Third World's $1.3 trillion debt.
   The lengthy negotiations apparently snagged, and Bush tried to
give them a boost by offering Mexico a temporary loan of $1 billion
to $2 billion. The offer appeared to be aimed at showing banks and
other creditor nations the United States would put its money where
its mouth is.
   For Mexico, an agreement would mean both money and a
psychological boost, two elements needed to reignite growth. Mexico
owes $107.4 billion and maintains that its economy is hobbled
because it must spend $16 billion every year to pay the interest and
principal.
   Mexico wants to reduce those payments by $7 billion, money that
could then be invested in industrial expansion to provide jobs.
Mexico has one million young people entering the job market every
year, creating tremendous social pressure _ some of which is
relieved by emigration to the United States.
   What can happen when a social system is under stress was seen
earlier this year when rioting broke out in Caracas, Venezuela, and
food stores were looted in Argentina.
   One private economist compared Mexico to a family whose loan
payments leave little left over even for basics like rent, food or
transportation. The family cuts spending and tries to increase its
income to avoid taking on more loans, but all its money goes into
the loan payments and it remains poor.
   Mexico incurred most of its debt between 1976 and 1982, when
eager banks pressed money on a nation that thought oil had made it
rich. But the price of oil crashed and growth in Mexico for the past
six years has averaged about zero. The buying power of the average
paycheck has been cut in half.
   ``When we talk about growth, it means to stop the fall in buying
power, to stop the process of impoverishment of Mexican society,''
said Jacobo Zaidenweber, a textile manufacturer who is president of
the U.S.-Mexico Chamber of Commerce.
   To turn the situation around requires investment. That's where
foreign debt reduction comes in.
   ``If a satisfactory agreement with respect to the debt is
reached, the necessary conditions to resume growth will be there,''
said Nora Lustig, an economics professor at the Colegio de Mexico
and a visiting fellow at the Brookings Institution in Washington.
   The agreement being discussed by the banks and Mexico calls for
approximately 35 percent of Mexico's debt to be written off and for
other adjustments in the debt structure to reduce the load.
   Some banks are reportedly asking for a clause that would increase
payments once Mexico's economy improves, but upping payments might
also cut off a recovery.
   Part of what Mexico gains will go to buying back debt at a
discount, economists say. The rest can be used for investment in
infrastructure that could prime the pump for the private sector.
   With fewer payments to make, the government will need to borrow
less money. That will put less pressure on domestic credit markets
and make more money available for the private sector at lower rates.
   Increased confidence would attract foreign investment and,
perhaps even more important, help bring back billions invested
abroad by wealthy Mexicans. Capital flight, according to recent
reports, has already ceased.
   Zaidenweber said a debt agreement will help him expand his
textile plants to compete with imports and increase exports.
   ``We have to grow to lower costs and get more modern equipment to
increase quality,'' he said.
   The government has set the stage for recovery with a program that
has pushed free-market reforms. Salinas has been a driving force
there, first as budget director, now as president.
   Nevertheless, Bank of Mexico director Miguel Mancera was cautious.
   ``The resources of the country are scarce. It's evident there
isn't enough for everything we would like to do,'' the daily El
Financiero quoted him as saying.
   ``Recovery will most likely be slow in the beginning,'' Ms.
Lustig said, ``but we might get a surprise.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
