<FIRST>r a AM-IndianRemains     07-15 0381</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Indian Remains,0391</SECOND>
<HEAD>Indian Bones to be Reburied at Wounded Knee After Symposium</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOSEPH KEENAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SIOUX FALLS, S.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The remains of ancient Seminole Indians
dug up in Florida will be reburied at Wounded Knee next month in a
ceremony to be conducted by members of the Oglala Sioux Tribe.
   The ceremony is scheduled for Aug. 11, at the Wounded Knee
Cemetery where about 200 Indians killed by U.S. troops in 1890 are
buried.
   The reburial of the prehistoric remains will follow a symposium
on archaeological ethics and the treatment of the dead to be held at
the University of South Dakota in Vermillion, said Larry Zimmerman,
a USD professor.
   Included in the 1,200 pounds of remains are pieces of pottery and
the dirt that was unearthed along with the bone fragments.
   ``The Florida earth will be with them,'' Zimmerman said.
   The remains, originally dug up by researchers and later given to
the Seminoles, were sent to the university by tribal members four
years ago under the condition that they not be used for scienctific
study, he said. Recently, Seminole tribe members asked USD officials
to give the remains to members of the Oglala Tribe for burial.
   The Oglalas make up the majority of the population on the Pine
Ridge Indian Reservation where Wounded Knee is located. But remains
from other distant Indian tribes have in recent years been sent to
Wounded Knee for burial.
   The issue of reburial has become a heated topic in archaeological
circles over the last decade. It's a subject that is often boiled
down to a case of science vs. religion, Zimmerman said.
   ``The whole issue of reburial is an issue that started primarily
in Australia and among native American Indians,'' he said. ``What's
happened over the last decade and a half is (indigenous peoples)
have become more politically active on this issue and see it as a
two-pronged concern.
   ``Is it a violation of religious freedom ... and who gets to use
these remains and where do they put them?''
   ``It isn't science vs. religion, it is who controls the past,''
he said.
   Archaelogists from about 20 countries and representatives from
North American Indian tribes and other indigenous people from around
the world are expected to attend the meeting.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
