<FIRST>r i AM-Netherlands-Spying     07-15 0264</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Netherlands-Spying,0274</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dentist Accused of Spying for Soviets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMSTELVEEN, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A dentist was accused of passing
state secrets to the Soviet Union after police found military
hardware and classified documents in his apartment, newspapers
reported Saturday.
   The 47-year-old man allegedly spied for the Soviet military
intelligence service, GRU, over an eight-year period, according to
the reports.
   The man, who runs an import-export business in addition to his
dental practice in this Amsterdam suburb, was arrested May 17 when
he was about to fly out of the country, the press reports said. They
said the man was released last week pending charges.
   Neither the man nor his firm was identified in any of the
reports, in line with Dutch media practice on police and judicial
cases.
   The Amsterdam newspaper De Volkskrant said police and
investigators of the Dutch Domestic Security Service found large
numbers of classified documents on military products made by Dutch
firms inside the man's apartment.
   However, it was not clear from any of the reports what material
the man allegedly passed to the Soviets, or how much damage the
activities had caused.
   The Interior Ministry, which is responsible for counterespionage,
was closed and not immediately available for comment.
   According to De Volkskrant, the papers found in the apartment
related to various kinds of high-technology military products,
including computer systems.
   If convicted of espionage, the man could face a 15-year prison
term.
   Dutch officials have repeatedly said the GRU and its civilian
counterpart, the KGB, have been stepping up their espionage efforts,
especially in the field of advanced technology.
</TEXT>
