<FIRST>r w AM-DrugPlan     07-15 0321</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drug Plan,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>EDS: For release 5:30 p.m. EDT, TIME set by source</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bentsen Wants Rural Areas Included In Drug-Control Blueprint</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The national anti-drug strategy due out this
fall must look beyond the big cities and address the rapid spread of
the cocaine derivative crack to rural areas, Sen. Lloyd Bentsen said
Saturday.
   Bentsen said he is asking national drug control director William
Bennett, who is drawiing up the anti-drug blueprint, to include
``measures to combat the serious and growing problem of drug abuse
in smaller towns and the rural countryside.''
   The Texas Democrat said he wants to be sure the Drug Enforcement
Administration ``doesn't limit its efforts to just the big dealers
and the big cities, that we include rural and small towns too.''
   In one rural Texas area, authorities report an 80 percent
increase in crack cases in just one year, Bentsen said.
   ``If you ignore that kind of an increase you do so at your own
peril,'' Bentsen said in his letter to Bennett. ``It's absolutely
imperative that we have an overall program that takes care of not
just the large cities but the small towns, rural areas in addition.''
   Bennett must complete the first comprehensive national
drug-control plan by Sept. 5.
   Bentsen said he was concerned about a recent DEA memorandum that
said crack dealers in smaller communities ``do not merit full
federal investigative efforts'' since they typically limit their
sales to small quantities.
   A DEA survey in 1986 found crack available in 28 states and the
District of Columbia. Another DEA survey in December 1987 found that
number had jumped to 45 states, Bentsen said.
   And while the survey noted that crack cocaine remained primarily
an inner city problem, it noted that ``recent seizures indicate that
crack has appeared in rural parts of Georgia, Mississippi,
Louisiana, Florida, Alabama, North Carolina, Delaware, Maryland, New
York and California.''
</TEXT>
