<DOCNO> AP890715-0071 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-89 1223EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u p AM-NYCMayoral Bjt   07-15 0909</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NYC Mayoral, Bjt,0935</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eight Weeks to Primary; Koch Makes it Official</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL STIEG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eight weeks before the primary Ed Koch's job is
clear: He either makes up ground fast or makes plans to step aside
for New York City's first black mayor, or its first Republican mayor
in two decades.
   ``Sixteen points in this day and age is not an insurmountable
margin by any means, as I was telling President Dukakis,'' quipped
David Garth, Koch's media adviser, on Friday.
   Garth was as surprised as anyone Thursday when Koch chose a
midday radio talk show to announce officially his candidacy for an
unprecedented fourth term. Not that there was any doubt _ he made
his intentions obvious last year and started television ads this
month.
   ``I think I've done a lot of good things. I've done a couple of
stupid things,'' said Koch, 64. ``I've done things that I would do
over and differently but that's water over the dam.
   ``I believe that my three terms will be perceived historically as
very good for the city of New York.''
   His opponents, and many pundits, think the outspoken Koch already
is history. David Dinkins, the Manhattan borough president, leads
Koch by 13 to 15 points in Democratic polls; the latest had him
ahead 45 percent to 31 percent. Getting more than 40 percent of the
vote in the Sept. 12 primary would enable Dinkins to avoid a primary
runoff.
   The likely Republican is former federal prosecutor Rudolph
Giuliani, who is far ahead of his GOP rival, cosmetics heir Ronald
Lauder. A Daily News-WABC-TV poll looking ahead to likely November
matchups puts Giuliani neck and neck with Dinkins, and ahead of
Koch, 49 percent to 33 percent.
   Two other Democrats, Comptroller Harrison Goldin and former
transit chief Richard Ravitch, remain stalled in single digits in
their primary bids.
   ``What's going on, I think, is the public is shutting its mind to
Ed Koch after 12 insulting years,'' said Mark Green, a Dinkins
adviser and former Senate candidate. ``I think I hear a collective,
`Enough, already.'''
   Koch received 78 percent of the vote last time he ran, back in
1985 when voters didn't have AIDS, crack and homelessness in mind.
His third term began with a corruption scandal, now all but
overshadowed by more pressing human problems.
   ``Do you know anyone who has solved AIDS or solved drugs or
housing in this country?'' Koch asks.
   His issue-oriented TV ads, featuring regular folks, carry the
slogan ``He tackles the tough ones'' in what is ``still the second
toughest job in America.''
   That still leaves corruption, crime, education and race _ this
last issue possibly crucial. Koch rankled blacks with his criticism
of the Rev. Jesse Jackson in last year's presidential primary, and
73 percent of blacks polled say they favor Dinkins, the first black
with a real shot at the mayor's mansion.
   The 62-year-old Dinkins, a relatively quiet, conciliatory
politician, delivered 135,386 signatures to the Board of Elections
on Thursday, far more than he needed and more than three times what
Koch collected.
   ``I'm sure he's pretty good at arithmetic and he would recognize
that this reflects an awful lot of support, a broad base,'' Dinkins
said.
   Said Koch, who began his political career as a reformer, but
twice was reelected with the backing of Democratic powers: ``He's
the machine candidate. What would you expect?''
   There have been other ironies so far in the campaign.
   Giuliani, 45, who built his reputation busting Wall Streeters,
mobsters and corrupt officials, found himself last week defending
the hiring of three lawyers who admitted having used drugs.
   Koch, of all people, paraphrased Jackson in Thursday's
announcement: ``I don't think God is finished with me yet and I want
to do more for this city.''
   Then there is Lauder's multimillion-dollar television onslaught,
in which a voice dripping with disgust calls Giuliani a liberal.
   A complicating factor in the race is the existence in New York of
small Conservative and Liberal parties, which enable candidates to
run even if they lose one of the two major primaries.
   Giuliani has already been endorsed by the Liberal Party, as was
Republican John Lindsay in 1965, and would run on that ticket in
addition to the GOP ticket if he wins in September.
   But Giuliani's stance against abortion has reduced his support,
the Daily News-WABC-TV poll indicated. Gays have criticized his
opposition to Koch's proposal to extend paid time off to city
employees grieving deaths of live-in companions.
   Lauder, who entered the race at the urging of Republican Sen.
Alfonse D'Amato, a rival of Giuliani, will likely remain in the race
on the Conservative line, and the votes he would get could hurt
Giuliani in a close general election.
   For his part, Garth says Koch has been creeping up in the polls,
from the mid-20s to the low 30s. ``My feeling is he's bottomed out
and is now moving up,'' Garth said, adding that polls don't show
Dinkins' supporters as particularly ardent.
   ``The way this business usually works, once you make that turn
and start to come back, you gather momentum,'' he said.
   Green said Koch is behind ``because he's an insult artist, yet
the more he now attacks Dave Dinkins, the more he reminds people
what they like least about him. I don't see how he gets out of this
box.''
   Countered Garth: ``There's no way to kill the spirit in him.''
  
</TEXT>
