<DOCNO> AP890715-0073 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-89 1226EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p AM-DetroitMayor     07-15 0914</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Detroit Mayor,0938</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four More Years for Coleman Young?</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-NYC Mayoral, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GRETEL WIKLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Coleman Young is preparing to announce
whether he will run for a fifth term this week as even some of his
supporters say he should step down at age 71.
   Eight weeks remain before the Sept. 12 non-partisan primary when
voters will select two candidates for a Nov. 7 runoff.
   Young, the city's first black mayor, is expected to announce his
plans Tuesday. He has hinted for months that he would run but left
open the possibility he would retire.
   ``If I announce, then I will announce when I announce,'' Young
said, a comment typical in tone of his chilly relations with
reporters, which his aides blame in part on media racism.
   Young, if he does run for another four-year term, would enter as
the solid front-runner, able to cite progress in areas such as
integrating the police force but also in spite of an array of
problems facing the city.
   He has a largely untapped campaign fund estimated at $5 million,
and is considered to hold a commanding lead over accountant Thomas
Barrow, who won the right to face him in the runoff four years ago
and is expected to do so again this year. Barrow reportedly has less
than $300,000 available for his campaign.
   Young, a former union organizer, has been in office since 1973,
the same year Tom Bradley of Los Angeles and Maynard Jackson of
Atlanta came to power in the early generation of big-city black
mayors.
   Barrow, 40, is founder and president of Michigan's largest
minority-owned accounting firm and a nephew of the late boxing great
Joe Louis. He received only 39 percent of the vote when he ran
against Young in 1985, but this year has been campaigning
door-to-door, while Young schedules about four public appearances a
week, nonchalantly skipping some of them.
   Other challengers include Detroit City Council President Erma
Henderson and longshots Charles Costa and James A. Williams Sr. The
filing deadline for candidates is July 25.
   Barrow and the others blame Young for the continuing decline of
Detroit's neighborhoods. Opponents say Young has concentrated on pet
downtown development projects at the expense of neighborhood upkeep
and services.
   And some longtime supporters, including Detroit's veteran black
congressmen John Conyers and George Crockett, also say it is time
for Detroit to have a new mayor.
   Crockett said he thinks Young should step down for his own
health, though Young has no outward signs of decline. Crockett, who
turns 80 next month, said he can give a younger man such advice
because he has fewer problems in Congress than Young has as mayor.
   Conyers was more outspoken, accusing the mayor of arrogance and
saying he has ``an unbroken record of personal and political
mistakes in the last few years.''
   ``Coleman's dead,'' Conyers said. ``It's time for him to go.'' He
said the mayor ``has lost sight of serving the people and has
created a political machine interested only in its own power.''
Conyers denies his comments are meant to promote a candidacy by
brother Nathan, a Detroit businessman. Nathan Conyers also denies he
has any interest in being mayor.
   Young, an ardent civil rights activist in this predominantly
black city, seemed to emerge unscathed politically last year after
criticizing the Rev. Jesse Jackson's presidential campaign, saying a
black man had no legitimate chance of winning and backing
Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis.
   But the mayor has other problems.
   Detroit's population has dropped from about 2 million in 1950 to
about 1 million today. The flight to outlying suburbs has left
behind thousands of boarded-up, burned-out houses that attract drug
dealers and other crime. Some fed-up residents, tired of waiting for
city demolition crews, have even torn down abandoned houses
themselves.
   Though Young's opponents have avoided mention of it, Young also
faces a paternity suit filed against him by Annivory Calvert, a
former assistant director in Detroit's Department of Public Works
who now lives in California.
   Young, who is single, at first denied the child was his. But in
May, blood tests proved he was the father of Ms. Calvert's
6-year-old son, Joel Loving. The mayor is paying $200 a week in
child support until the court sets a final amount.
   Other issues facing the mayor include:
   _Detroit's trash-burning incinerator, which has angered
environmentalists who say pollution standards for the $420 million
project to create energy by burning wastes are too low.
   _A deal involving the city's acquisition of land for a $1 billion
Chrysler Corp. assembly plant, which is being investigated by a
federal grand jury amid charges the city paid $40 million for used
machinery worth $2 million in condemned buildings on the plant site.
There's no suggestion that Young himself is suspected of criminal
wrongdoing.
   _Young's hostile relations with reporters, and negative coverage
that the mayor's staff blames on institutional racism. Young
rebuffed numerous requests for an interview by The Associated Press.
   Young has been particularly unhappy with local coverage of the
police force, a once-predominantly white department whose racial
integration has been a source of pride for the mayor.
   Fred Martin, Young's chief executive assistant, said the makeover
of the force was ignored by local media. Specifically, Martin said,
a group of newspaper columnists ``constantly dump on the mayor.''
   ``We do think there is a little different standard for Coleman
Young,'' he said. ``I'm not saying that it is conscious or
deliberate.''
</TEXT>
