<DOCNO> AP890715-0074 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-89 1246EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-HUD-Demery Bjt   07-15 1060</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-HUD-Demery, Bjt,900</SECOND>
<HEAD>Justice Investigates Questionable Grants By Former Agency Official</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   HUD has turned over to the Justice Department
records that show a former top official passed over
financially-strapped housing projects in favor of doling out
emergency funds to a one-time business associate and donors to his
pet charity.
   The Department of Housing and Urban Development's inspector
general concluded in a March audit that at least 11 of 25 projects
funded through the emergency set-aide program in 1987 and 1988 did
not meet agency guidelines. Several well-connected developers
received multiple awards from the fund.
   Seven projects that exceeded guidelines were bypassed; they
eventually went under and had to be taken over by HUD, which over
time will cost the government millions of dollars, the auditors
concluded.
   HUD investigators said those decisions were made by Thomas T.
Demery, who at the time was HUD's assistant secretary for housing.
He left the agency last year and opened a consulting business but
has been beleaguered of late with questions about his actions at HUD.
   The department is the focus of internal, congressional and
Justice Department investigations of fraud, mismanagement and
influence-peddling during President Reagan's tenure.
   Demery, 39, in a brief interview Thursday, denied favoritism
played a role in any funding decisions. ``It was all done on the
merits,'' he said.
   But department officials, in the report that HUD sources said has
been forwarded to Justice as part of its investigation of the
troubled housing agency, said ``assistance was provided to projects
that were neither approvable under the regulations nor demonstrated
an emergency need.'' The sources spoke on condition they not be
identified.
   The Section 8 loan management set aside fund is used to help
struggling housing projects that already have some type of
government financing. Guidelines allow the emergency assistance in
cases when low occupancy or other problems have caused severe
financial problems. The infusion of HUD money, through the use of
low-income rent subsidies, is designed to prevent a more costly
default.
   The emergency accounts totaled $42 million during the two-year
audit period; $36 million of that went to the 11 questionable
projects chosen by Demery for help.
   Of those 11, six did not demonstrate a cash-flow problem and the
five others were ineligible for funding because of poor maintenance,
management or other problems, HUD investigators concluded. In
addition, some of the projects had not even applied locally for
funding, and in other cases local HUD officials had rejected
applications, the auditors said.
   The investigators said they could find no documentation to
support Demery's decisions.
   What can be found through review of the HUD records, Demery's
financial disclosure statements and other records is that Demery had
past ties to at least one of the developers who got emergency
funding. Several others were contributors to FOOD for Africa, a
Michigan-based charity Demery helped found.
   A separate audit of a HUD rehabilitation program also found
scores of occasions in which FOOD donors won lucrative government
subsidies. Demery attended several fund-raisers for the charity that
were hosted by developers. He has repeatedly denied that the
donations affected his HUD decisions.
   A review of Demery's telephone and appointment logs by The
Associated Press also indicated that several of the developers who
got emergency funding called Demery several times in the period that
those and other funding decisions about their HUD projects were made.
   _ Emergency funding went to two projects owned by Robert
Rohlwing, with whom Demery in 1984 was involved in a small mortgage
venture. One of the projects was poorly maintained and the other
scored zero on a test for need, auditors said. Demery awarded
Rohlwing $342,000 immediately, with the possibility he could get up
to $1.7 million over several years. Rohlwing donated $1,000 to FOOD
in 1987.
   Demery's phone logs, obtained through The Freedom of Information
Act, show numerous calls from Rohlwing. Rohlwing did not return a
reporter's telephone call to his Chicago office last week.
   _ Another name found a number of times on the logs is that of
Allan Bird, a developer of more than 100 HUD projects who got
$405,000 in emergency funding for an apartment complex in Boston
that failed quality standards. To make repairs, Bird got an
additional $1 million from HUD. He donated $2,500 to FOOD in 1987.
   _ Demery awarded $142,000 to the Amy Jo Manor in Grand Rapids,
Mich., a project auditors said did not meet requirements for
emergency aid. The project is owned by a group called PM One Inc.,
which donated $2,000 to FOOD. A related company also donated to the
charity.
   The president of PM One Inc., Daniel Armstead, did not return a
telephone call to his Michigan office.
   Demery in 1984 received a fee of at least $5,000 from a related
company, PMI Inc., for consulting work. At the time he was a
Michigan real estate consultant and mortgage broker who did some HUD
contracting work.
   _ One of the owners of another projects that received emergency
assistance, Jeffrey I. Friedman, also donated $1,000 to FOOD in
October 1987. The auditors, however, did not question the
eligibility of that project, Somerset West apartments in North
Royalton, Ohio, which received $180,000 from Demery.
   _ Seven of the 25 projects given emergency funding over the
two-year period were in Demery's home state of Michigan. His phone
logs show he kept close ties with his business associates there,
often receiving several calls a day from Michigan developers.
   Irving Seligman, a Southfield, Mich., developer who got emergency
assistance for three projects that auditors said were not eligible,
said the frequency of the awards to Michigan was not due to
favoritism but because of struggling developments in low-income
areas.
   Demery approved $426,000 in emergency funding for two projects
Seligman owned in Taylor, Mich., over the objections of local HUD
and government officials who said the area already had too much
subsidized housing. The third project, in Phoenix, got $347,000 even
though it already had more subsidized apartments than HUD guidelines
allowed, the auditors said.
   Seligman said he knew Demery from his HUD-related work in
Michigan in the early 1980s and spoke to him often. But he said he
did not believe he had any special influence with Demery, who has
said he approved the funding because he thought the local objections
stemmed from a personality clash.
</TEXT>
