<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-89 1322EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-HongKong-China     07-15 0614</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hong Kong-China,0635</SECOND>
<HEAD>Director of Left-Wing Hong Kong Paper Fired By Beijing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a heavy-handed attempt to exert communist
control over a Hong Kong newspaper, China on Saturday fired the
publisher of a pro-Beijing paper that had criticized the crackdown
on student-led demonstrators in Beijing.
   The publisher of the Chinese-backed Wen Wei Po newspaper, Lee
Tze-chung, called the dismissal ``illegal'' and said he would fight
to stay at the post.
   The Communist government, acting through its official Xinhua News
Agency, replaced Lee with Chen Bojian, a former Xinhua executive who
had been working at the paper about two years.
   A day earlier, Lee had tried to fire Chen for his attempts to
stop the paper from criticizing the June 3-4 military assault on the
pro-democracy demonstrators.
   A source close to the 78-year-old Lee said he planned to go to
court to challenge the action.
   Zhang Junsheng, vice-director of Xinhua in Hong Kong, announced
Lee's dismissal after an all-night meeting of the paper's editorial
board, which Lee did not attend.
   He said Lee's firing was legal because Wen Wei Po was ``backed by
Chinese investment'' and therefore Xinhua had the right to ``manage
the newspaper.'' China gives the paper an estimated $1.3 million a
year and Chinese companies hold the bulk of its stock.
   Zhang cited a 4-year-old resignation letter written by Lee as
evidence of the legality of the dismissal.
   ``Now, we have decided to accept his resignation,'' he said.
   Lee's dismissal marks the latest in a series of attempts by
Beijing to reassert its control over left-wing publications in Hong
Kong and extend the current ideological campaign to this British
colony, which reverts to Chinese rule in 1997.
   After the military crackdown in Beijing, China lost all support
from Chinese-language magazines and papers in Hong Kong.
   Lee's newspaper changed its masthead from red to black in
mourning.
   ``Today, I can't be an accomplice to the murderers anymore,'' Lee
said in a television interview after the military assault.
   The statement marked the first time since the paper was founded
in 1948 that it had broken with the Communist Party.
   Support from the Hong Kong media is important for China because
many Hong Kong papers set the tone for public opinion in Chinese
communities worldwide. Many also are smuggled into China.
   Since the crackdown began, Chinese officials have repeatedly told
Hong Kong residents not to ``interfere'' in China's domestic affairs
by publishing critical accounts of the crackdown or helping the
movement for democratic reforms.
   Wen Wei Po continued to refer to Chinese leaders Deng Xiaoping
and Li Peng as ``a gang of thieves.'' Lee had also reportedly been
exploring a plan to allow the paper to become independent from
Communist control.
   A group of American Chinese have formed an organization, Friends
of the Wen Wei Po, to raise funds for the paper.
   On Thursday, Lee and Chen battled over an article on the group.
Chen won out as Wen Wei Po published a report criticizing the
organization.
   In his statement, Lee blasted Chen's story, calling it ``nothing
but wanton insults.''
   Several editors of Hong Kong publications said Xinhua's actions
were disturbing because they constituted an infringement on a free
press.
   Hong Kong will return to Chinese rule in 1997 and China has
promised to keep the colony's free-wheeling social and capitalist
economic system intact for 50 years.
   ``But this type of action shows that it's all a farce,'' said Lee
Yi, publisher of The Nineties, an influential Chinese-language
magazine. ``We have a choice: Either report the news or become
Beijing's mouthpiece. Those of us who report the news had best get
out of town.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
