<FIRST>r i AM-AirStrike     07-15 0291</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Air Strike,0300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Strike by Technicians Delays Flights Across Europe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A strike by French air traffic control technicians
disrupted flight schedules Saturday throughout much of Western
Europe, causing delays of up to 10 hours on some flights, officials
said.
   Civil aviation officials at Orly Airport in Paris said the strike
by technicians, who maintain radars and other electronic equipment
used for takeoffs and landings, was scheduled to last until Monday.
It began Tuesday.
   Controllers were ordered to increase spacing between flights as a
safety measure.
   The domestic airline Air Inter predicted delays on about 30 of
its 240 flights Saturday, and the backups disrupted flights
elsewhere in Europe.
   The technicians are seeking increased staffing and changes in
career promotion ladders to match those of air traffic controllers.
   The Transport Ministry said technicians should be satisfied with
results of negotiations in October, which it said resulted in an
agreement giving them ``advantages comparable to those of the other
categories'' of air traffic control employees.
   In London, the Civil Aviation Authority said French controllers
had cut the number of British flights handled from 54 to a half
dozen per hour, and British air traffic controllers were offering to
reroute some flights.
   The dispute delayed British flights to Spain, Portugal and North
Africa by up to 5{ hours. Flights to and from Italy also were
affected.
   The Spanish flag carrier Iberia canceled 16 flights to and from
European countries, and flights out of the resort island of Palma
were delayed up to 10 hours, said a Spanish air official.
   The French Transport Ministry issued a statement saying ``maximal
conditions of safety are still being fulfilled'' even though
controllers were not able to use some equipment normally used to
track flights.
</TEXT>
