<DOCNO> AP890715-0083 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-89 1338EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru   07-15 0576</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0493,0595</SECOND>
<HEAD>Syrians, Christian Clash Amid Shiite Battles and Power Blackout</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 8 grafs to UPDATE with 1 dead, 19 wounded, shelling
intensifying; picks up 5th pvs, `A police...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian and Christian gunners battled with
howitzers and mortars around the capital Saturday as rival Shiite
Moslem militias fought in the alleyways of the city's southern slums.
   The state electricity authority declared a power blackout in
Beirut and in the 310-square-mile Christian enclave northeast of the
city Saturday after it ran out of fuel for its main generating plant
in Christian east Beirut.
   Police said one person was killed and at least 19 people were
wounded in the artillery duels.
   That raised the casualty toll from the 17-week confrontation
between Christian army commander Gen. Michel Aoun's forces and the
Syrians to 417 killed and 1,646 wounded.
   Police said the Syrian-Christian artillery duels intensified in
the afternoon as shells rained on Beirut's Moslem and Christian
sections.
   ``It has been almost two months since we were pounded with such
intensity,'' said a resident of the Christian district of Sen El-Fil.
   Forty rockets hit the neighborhood simultaneously, he said,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Police also reported machine-gun and mortar clashes across
Beirut's dividing Green Line and in the mountains southeast of the
capital.
   A police spokesman said one person was killed and four were
wounded in a four-hour firefight between the pro-Syrian Amal militia
and the Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God.
   The rival factions battled with automatic weapons and
rocket-propelled grenades in the narrow alleys of south Beirut.
   The spokesman, who cannot be named under standing regulations,
said the fighting ended when Syrian troops intervened at 4 a.m.
   By police count, 561 people have been killed and 1,554 wounded
since Amal and Hezbollah began fighting in Beirut and south Lebanon
last April for dominance of Lebanon's 1.2 million Shiites.
   The police spokesman said Syrian howitzers deployed in Moslem
west Beirut shelled a 28-mile stretch of the Christian coastline
north of Beirut and key positions manned by Aoun's army in the
mountains overlooking Beirut.
   He said shells fell around the ports of Jounieh and Byblos and
the Christian towns of Hadath and Kfar Sheema on the southeastern
edge of the war-divided capital.
   Smoke billowed from the wooded slopes that overlook Beirut as the
sound of exploding shells echoed across the battered city.
   Aoun's gunners responded by shelling the Syrian batteries along
the main seaside boulevard in west Beirut and Syrian positions in
the Druse Moslem villages of Shweifat and Aitat, the spokesman said.
   The Syrians shell the coastline north of Beirut daily to enforce
a blockade of Christian ports and prevent Aoun from receiving
shipments of war material and other supplies.
   The blockade has caused a serious fuel shortage in the Christian
sector, where some 1 million people are trapped.
   The electricity authority said it will continue to provide power
to water pumping stations, hospitals and communications centers for
two hours a day.
   The fighting between the Syrians and Aoun's forces broke out
March 8, two days after Aoun blockaded illegal ports run by
Syrian-backed Moslem militias south of Beirut.
   He charged that the militia ports robbed the badly depleted state
treasury of about $100 million a year in lost customs fees.
   The Syrians, who back Moslems demanding an equal share of power
with the traditionally dominant Christians, responded by besieging
the Christian enclave.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
