<FIRST>r i AM-GulfOilSpill     07-15 0340</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gulf Oil Spill,0351</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tanker Damaged in Indian Ocean Collision Leaks Oil Off U.A.E.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ABU DHABI, United Arab Emirates (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tanker spilled more than
1.6 million gallons of oil into the Persian Gulf and Indian Ocean
and has been turned away from three ports since a collision last
month, shipping sources said Saturday.
   A 60-mile-long oil slick was heading toward the Indian coast,
said the sources, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The Maltese-flagged 32,000-ton Puppy was anchored Saturday in
international waters off Khor Fakkan, and several tugboats were to
be sent to transfer the oil from the leaking tanks, the sources said.
   Khor Fakkan, a Persian Gulf port 200 miles south of Abu Dhabi,
refused to permit the Puppy into port because of the leak.
   The June 28 collision occurred in the Indian Ocean between the
Puppy, managed by the Geneva-based Acomarit Services Maritimes, and
the 24,597-ton bulk carrier Quince, managed by a Hong Kong-based
firm.
   The accident, about 700 miles southwest of Bombay, ruptured two
cargo tanks aboard the Puppy, which was on its way from Egypt with a
load of crude oil for Singapore.
   After the accident, Bombay refused to let the Puppy dock because
of the leaking oil.
   Meanwhile, the tanker spilled 1.2 million gallons into the Indian
Ocean, creating a slick more than 60 miles long and 12 miles wide,
the sources said.
   Sea currents were pushing the slick toward India's Kerala coast,
and it was expected to reach there within 10 days.
   The tanker, pulled by a tugboat, headed for Khor Fakkan and
Fujairah, another United Arab Emirates port, but was told to stay
off the coast and wait for help.
   Capt. Roger Saunders, Fujairah's port director, said the tanker
was ``diverted to international waters'' five days ago and anchored
about 50 miles off Khor Fakkan.
   ``The delay in the ... transfer of the oil ... has increased the
danger of the oil slick growing,'' one source said. ``A thin oil
slick was noticed when the stricken vessel anchored five days ago.''
</TEXT>
