<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-89 1456EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-DioxinScare     07-15 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dioxin Scare,0360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Bans Sale Of Dioxin-Tainted Milk And Meat Products</HEAD>
<DATELINE>THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has banned the sale
of milk and meat products from farms near two large waste
incinerators after foodstuffs from the farms were found to be
contaminated by dioxin.
   The decision was announced in a letter to Parliament late Friday
and followed tests showing that the milk contained three times the
amount of dioxin considered normal, according to George Dankmeyer, a
Heath Ministry spokesman.
   The official described the measures as ``precautionary'' and said
there was no immediate danger to public health.
   However, Dankmeyer added that consumers drinking the contaminated
milk on a daily basis would ultimately take in more dioxin than is
considered safe, he said.
   The government also ordered the waste furnaces to take stricter
anti-pollution measures and was considering suing them for damages,
he said.
   Dioxin is a highly toxic chemical contaminant that can be
released into the atmosphere as a byproduct of waste combustion. It
has been used in chemical warfare.
   At issue is the milk and meat produce of 16 dairy farms
surrounding the Rijnmond Waste Disposal Center near Rotterdam, the
nation's largest combustion furnace for domestic waste.
   The annual milk output of those farms is about 1 million gallons
but there was no immediate word how much of the tainted milk had
been sold or over what period.
   The government announced similar measures for farms in the area
of a waste furnace near Amsterdam after theoretical calculations
showed the same level of dioxin pollution was likely there,
Dankmeyer said.
   Tests on produce from the Amsterdam site still need to be
completed, he said, adding that 10 similar combustion furnaces
elsewhere in the country were believed safe.
   Milk from the two sites will be taken to a specially designated
dairy factory, where the milkfat, in which dioxin accumulates, will
be skimmed off and destroyed. The remainder will be converted into
powdered milk, Dankmeyer said.
   Meat originating from any of the stricken farms will also be
destroyed, said Dankmeyer, adding that farmers will be fully
compensated.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
