<FIRST>u i AM-Summit-Media     07-15 0556</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Summit-Media,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Summit, Bicentennial Draw Media Hordes to Paris</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLINE ALLEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Slung with I.D. tags and touting lenses worth more
than the per capita income of poorer countries, 6,000 journalists
descended on Paris to report on the summit of the world's seven
richest nations and revel in the glamour of the French bicentennial
celebrations.
   The summit and the media circus moved into the barely-completed
Arche de La Defense, the glittering 35-story cube that crowns the La
Defense business district on Paris' western edge.
   Camera crews relished the panorama from the 54-step climb to the
marble base of the Arche, a structure that forced writers to dust
off their architectural vocabulary: the consensus settled on
``post-modernist.''
   Close-mouthed about the cost, the French have splashed out the
hospitality for the more than 30 heads of state and the journalists
who traced their every move. Open bars and four 500-seat tented
pavillions at the Arche offered 23,000 lavish meals to ravenous
reporters during the summit weekend.
   The timing of the summit _ after President Bush's Eastern
European tour _ and the bicentennial festivities have brought out
the media stars.
   ABC's Peter Jennings, CBS's Dan Rather and NBC's Tom Brokaw all
broadcast from famous Parisian sites.
   The festivities and the summit stretched logistics organizers to
the limit.
   ``Each time we try to do smarter and better with less people,''
says Lloyd Siegel of NBC, which has a team of about 50 on the
mission. Like other media organizations, NBC has added staff but
mainly to handle the bicentennial side or the economic issues.
   The military parades, dance extravaganzas and the fireworks
bursting over the summer crowds have provided a colorful finish to
Bush's headline-grabbing swing through Poland and Hungary.
   ABC network originated its Business World show from here.
   ABC's Good Morning America also broadcast a special on the
bicentennial from Notre Dame cathedral, while NBC originated Today
from the Quai de Tournelle.
   Each of the three major networks lined up top Bush adminstration
officials for its Sunday morning talk shows _ Secretary of State
James A. Baker III on ABC, national security adviser Brent Scowcroft
on CBS and White House Chief of Staff John Sununu on NBC.
   For a crew from Japan Broadcasting Corporation, the two events
complement each other.
   ``What President (Francois) Mitterrand was trying to do involving
the summit in the bicentennial makes it more festive,'' said Takemi
Shiga. ``But I think if the summit was not held in Paris the
bicentennial would not be so much reported.''
   Some reporters grumbled about the readiness of the French for the
media hordes.
   Crews cited delayed accreditation, the half-finished state of the
Arche, which lead to power cuts and communications problems, the
endless security checks and the travel arrangements between assorted
press centers and hotels.
   Reporters traveling in the U.S. presidential motorcade got
separated from the Bush limousine more than once, while other groups
followed the president for seven-hour stretches without even seeing
him.
   But the White House press room, esconced in the Meridien Hotel,
has allowed journalists from other countries and non-U.S. agencies
to join expanded travel pools.
   ``The problems we have had here are unavoidable,'' said a French
journalist who did not want to be named. ``Things would be simpler
for foreigners who spoke even a few words of French.''
</TEXT>
