<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-89 1507EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Summit-Protocol 1stLdWritethru a0546 07-15 0699</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Summit-Protocol, 1st Ld Writethru, a0546,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds. Subs graf 7, bgng, ``But that, to CORRECT that Bush had precedence
as head of state; picks up 8th graf, ``The official</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL GOLDSMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Britain's Margaret Thatcher and Zaire's Mobutu
Sese Seko arrived to view the lavish military parade on the
Champs-Elysees marking France's bicentennial, they automatically
strode up to the front row, befitting their place as leaders of
their countries.
   Embarrassed French officials had to show them to their seats _ at
the back of the bullet-proof stand.
   The seating order, the officials explained, was dictated by
protocol.
   But how that magic formula is determined remains a mystery.
   The summit of the world's seven richest nations, the simultaneous
meeting of some two dozen Third World leaders and the celebrations
for the 200th anniversary of the French Revolution were all ruled by
protocol.
   A Foreign Ministry spokesman said Saturday the seven were led by
France, the host nation, followed in order by the United States,
Britain, West Germany, Canada, Ialy and Japan. The spokesman said
the order was determined by the years the leader had held his office.
   Protocol placed President Bush, barely six months into his term,
ahead of the others because he, like Mitterrand, is a head of state
and not merely a head of government, like Mrs. Thatcher and the rest.
   The official could not give any motivation for the order in which
the leaders of the other 27 countries _ most of whom went home
Saturday _ were ranked.
   Protocol was invented by the French before the French Revolution
as a set of rules for the behavior of diplomats.
   As host, French President Francois Mitterrand was able to use
protocol to get his message across, putting emphasis where he felt
it was due and, perhaps, putting world leaders such as Thatcher in
their place.
   As master of ceremonies, Mitterrand was able to control events,
from how the heads of government lined up for the official
photograph to the order in which they made their getaways by
limousine.
   Mobutu, who was not invited but came anyway, is on the French
government's blacklist for his checkered human rights record.
   Wearing his trademark leopard skin cap, Mobutu strode to the
front row of every meeting, only to find he was seated
inconspicuously at the back.
   Mrs. Thatcher was booed by the French public Friday for recalling
the ``incredible terror'' of their hallowed revolution and likening
it to latter day exterminations in communist lands.
   Mrs. Thatcher had a place of honor on Mitterrand's left in the
formal group photo taken of the seven; Bush was on his right.
   ``We could not do anything else, since she was the only lady
among the leaders,'' a Foreign Ministry spokesman explained.
   But at the inauguration of the new opera house at the Bastille,
Mrs. Thatcher found she had to take a back seat with Mobutu, while
Bush was in front, alongside India's Rajiv Gandhi and Brazil's Jose
Sarney.
   At Friday's military parade, the British prime minister was among
the last allowed to leave the bulletproof enclosure encircling the
leaders. Japan's Uno was also in the rear guard.
   Mitterrand and his motocycle escort left first, as is the custom
for the host.
   But the arrangements for the others had not been made clear in
advance. So, for several minutes, the leaders sat on their red
velvet chairs not daring to move for fear of _ what else? _
upsetting protocol.
   When the order of departure was finally sorted out, President
Felix Houphouet-Boigny of the Ivory Coast, a leader of the
underprivileged countries, was first out of the gate, followed
swiftly by Bush.
   In the confusion, the leaders' cars got out of order and some
almost collided. President Omar Bongo of Gabon decided to return to
his hotel on foot.
   Mitterrand was unable to win approval of his idea for a
North-South summit of the nation's rich and poor countries.
   But he was able to ensure that the leaders of the poor nations
had plenty of opportunities to mix and mingle with the presidents
and prime ministers of the mighty seven. He threw them together at
every opportunity.
</TEXT>
