<FIRST>r a AM-TankerAground 1stLd-Writethru a0532 07-15 0254</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tanker Aground, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0532,0254</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Tanker Hits Bottom, No Damage To Hull</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with tanker refloated, to be inspected by
divers, CORRECTS amount of oil carried to 16.5 million gallons, sted 395,000
gallons; No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PASCAGOULA, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Chevron tanker carrying 16.5 million
gallons of crude oil ran aground 10 miles south of here, but there
was no oil leakage or damage to the vessel's hull, a Coast Guard
spokesman said Saturday.
   The 785-foot tanker, the R. Hal Dean, became stuck in mud about 6
p.m Friday and was refloated by 10:15 a.m. Saturday, said Cmdr.
James Gormanson of the Coast Guard office in Mobile, Ala. Five
tugboats were used.
   ``Beginning about 4:30 a.m., they took 125,000 barrels off the
vessel to raise the vessel from the mud,'' Gormanson said. ``No
spill was noted.''
   ``We know of no oil in the water,'' said Larry Shanks, manager of
operations at Chevron's Pascagoula refinery.
   The tanker had been en route to the refinery when it ran aground
near the junction of the Pascagoula and Horn Island channels. The
Coast Guard closed a channel while crews refloated the vessel.
   The tanker continued on to the refinery after being refloated.
Its hull will be inspected by divers before the ship puts out to sea
again, said Petty Officer Scott Green of Coast Guard's Mobile, Ala.,
office.
   The R. Hal Dean is a ``lightering vessel,'' which off-loads
supertankers in the Gulf and carries the crude oil to port, Shanks
said.
</TEXT>
