<FIRST>r i AM-Somalia     07-15 0436</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Somalia,0451</SECOND>
<HEAD>Residents Report More Shooting in Somallia's Capital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunfire rang through Somalia's capital on
Saturday for a second straight day, residents said, and police
increased the death toll to 23 from clashes between security forces
and religious demonstrators.
   Police said 59 people were wounded in Friday's clashes in
Somalia's capital, Mogadishu, when security forces opened fire on
what the government termed ``troublemakers hiding behind the banner
of religion.''
   It was unclear what caused the violence.
   The government Friday gave the death toll as 10. It did not
explain why the casualty count was increased Saturday.
   In Italy, the Foreign Ministry summoned the ambassador from
Somalia on Saturday to express its concern about the lives of
Italians in the country. The ministry also said a military plane had
flown from Mogadishu to Nairobi on Saturday with about 40 Italians
who asked to leave Somalia.
   Residents, who spoke by telephone, said shots were heard
periodically around the East African capital Saturday but that the
shooting lacked the intensity of Friday's clashes.
   The residents, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the city
was otherwise calm and that authorities lifted a 6 p.m-6 a.m. curfew.
   Somali President Mohamed Siad Barre, in a statement broadcast
over state radio and monitored in Nairobi, offered his condolences
to the relatives of victims and said the clashes were over and
``things were back to normal.''
   The government said Friday that security forces opened fire after
religious demonstrators attacked them with stones, knives and sticks.
   A resident contacted by telephone Friday said it appeared troops
had opened fire as Moslem worshipers left their place of prayer.
Islam is the state religion in the overwhelmingly pastoral,
impoverished nation of about 9 million.
   Friday is normally the Moslem Sabbath, but July 14 also was the
occasion for feast and celebration of the hajj, the Moslem
pilgrimage to the holy city of Mecca.
   There were reports during the week that several Moslem religious
leaders and other prominent citizens had been detained by
authorities, but it was not known whether the reported arrests were
related to the clashes.
   On July 9, a gunman killed Mogadishu's Roman Catholic bishop,
Salvatore Pietro Colombo. It was not known whether the disturbances
were connected to that incident. There are an estimated 2,000 Roman
Catholics in Somalia.
   Siad Barre, who has ruled since 1969, has not allowed journalists
to visit for more than a year.
   Since 1981, Somalia has battled the Somali National Movement,
which demands Barre's removal. Intensified fighting in the last 18
months has driven more than 200,000 Somalis into refugee camps in
neighboring Ethiopia.
</TEXT>
