<FIRST>r i AM-Israel     07-15 0458</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel,0473</SECOND>
<HEAD>Palestinian Killed; Slaying of Jew Linked to Uprising</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Masked Palestinians on Saturday reportedly
killed an Arab suspected of collaborating with Israeli authorities,
and police concluded that the slaying of an elderly Israeli man was
tied to the uprising.
   The army imposed curfews on the Nur-Shams refugee camp near the
West Bank town of Nablus and on several refugee camps and villages
in the Gaza Strip.
   Nine Palestinians were reported wounded in scattered clashes with
Israeli soldiers in the occupied lands. In Jerusalem, four Arabs
were injured in Israeli stone-throwing attacks, the national news
agency Itim said.
   In West Bank town of Qalqilya, masked Palestinians broke into the
house of Mohammed Yusef Abu Khader, 60, accused him of collaborating
with Israeli officials and fatally stabbed him, Arab journalists and
Israel radio said.
   The death brought to 564 the number of Palestinians killed in the
19-month uprising against Israeli rule in the West Bank and Gaza
Strip.
   Most victims died in army gunfire, but more than 70 have been
killed by Palestinians who accused them of being collaborators.
   Police said that two 16-year-old Palestinians confessed to
murdering Zalman Yosef Schlein, 64, in the southern Israeli town of
Gan Yavne on Friday.
   Israel radio said one of the teen-agers stabbed the elderly
Jewish man while the other hit him on the head with an iron bar.
   Initial reports had said Schlein was slain in a dispute over
money.
   But Uzi Sandouri, spokesman for the southern police district,
said the murder was ``a premeditated nationalist killing.'' Sandouri
told The Associated Press the two suspects, whose names were not
released, were members of an underground group in Gaza City's
Shajaiya quarter.
   Schlein's death brought to 36 the number of Israelis slain in the
uprising. Most of them were civilians.
   Arab hospital officials said a clash with soldiers left two
Palestinian teen-agers from Nur-Shams injured, one with serious
gunshot wounds to the chest and stomach. In Tulkarem refugee camp,
Israeli soldiers shot and wounded an 8-year-old boy in the thigh
with a plastic bullet, Arab doctors said.
   In the Gaza Strip, the army ordered all male residents of Beit
Hanoun aged 15 to 50 to gather at a local agricultural school while
the village was placed under curfew, Arab reports said.
   Youths who ran away from the village told Arab journalists
soldiers checked the residents' identity cards against computerized
lists and arrested at least 50 suspected ringleaders. The military
command said it was checking the report.
   At least six Palestinians were shot and wounded in clashes with
troops in Gaza's Jabaliya and Rafah refugee camps, Arab hospital
officials said.
   The army confirmed two wounded in the West Bank and three in Gaza.
</TEXT>
