<FIRST>r a AM-FireCenter     07-15 0509</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fire Center,0523</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fire Season Simmers After Two Week Send-off</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK WARBIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOISE, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After a frenzied two weeks to kick off the
West's wildfire season, activity scaled back to a simmer by week's
end at the federal Boise Interagency Fire Center.
   But old hands at the national command post know the slack is only
a lull between storms _ a chance to sharpen shovels, restock
supplies and rest before the next onslaught.
   High-tech sensors to detect lightning strikes offer clues, but
where fires will rage is beyond even the center's experts in
firefighting tactics, manpower allocation, weather forecasting and
logistics.
   ``All we can say for sure is conditions remain hot and dry. The
rest is up to Mother Nature,'' said spokesman Arnold Hartigan. ``We
are far from being out of the fire season yet.''
   The Boise center is the federal government's logistics and
support nerve center for firefighting activities across North
America.
   There were 33,388 fires reported nationwide to the Boise center
through Thursday. That was well below the 56,489 reported through
July 13 last year, when blazes across the northern Rockies were
beginning to spread rapidly through drought-parched brush and timber.
   Almost 6 million acres were burned last year, including more than
1 million acres of Yellowstone National Park, where flames changed
the famous landscape for generations. Federal agencies spent almost
$584 million on firefighting.
   This year's fires, although not as numerous, are bigger.
Nationwide, they had burned almost 130,000 acres more through
Thursday than the 1.1 million acres blackened by the same time in
1988.
   Officials say the reasons include large spring blazes in Florida
and the Southwest, barely accessible terrain and plentiful,
well-cured fuel after a number of years without fires in this
season's hot spots.
   The 1989 fires also are further south. The focus of fire activity
last summer was Wyoming, Montana, Idaho, Oregon and northern
California. This year it's Arizona, New Mexico, Colorado, Utah and
Southern California.
   ``It's where the drought is,'' Hartigan said. ``The pattern has
shifted southwest. But I'd have to say that almost all of the West,
with very few exceptions, is still not entirely recovered from four
years of drought.''
   As far east as Nebraska, where the impact of drought is more
often seen in withering corn fields, fire is taking its toll.
   But overall, the first assault of the 1989 fire season still
pales in comparison with the memory of 1988.
   About 12,500 firefighters were in the field at the height of
activity last week. There were about 30,000 during the first week of
September last year, including 5,600 Army and Marine troops.
   Hartigan said the help provided by those crews, primarily at
Yellowstone, gave fire bosses an extra tool they hope will be
unnecessary this summer.
   ``What we learned is military troops are physically fit, they're
disciplined and we can train them to do what we need to do in just a
couple of days,'' he said. ``We're not anticipating the need for
that, but we want to be prepared.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
