<DOCNO> AP890715-0101 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-89 1529EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Summit-Debt     07-15 0700</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Summit-Debt,670</SECOND>
<HEAD>White House Raises Possibility of Breakthrough in Mexico Debt Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mexico, test case for the United States' new
strategy to ease the foreign debt problem, may clinch a deal shortly
with bankers to trim its $100 billion loan portfolio, a White House
official said Saturday.
   ``It is in the dotting the `i' and crossing the `t' stage on some
of the tough details that are important both of Mexico and the
banks,'' John Sununu told reporters.
   Sununu, President Bush's chief of staff, raised the possibility
of an agreement by Sunday's conclusion of the economic summit of the
seven major industrialized nations in Paris.
   Bush and other officials want an early end to the talks with
Mexico to prove the viability of its new approach on the $1.3
trillion debt of developing nations. The strategy, marking a sharp
turn in American policy, emphasizes debt forgiveness or reduction
for the poorer nations.
   Finance ministers taking part in the summit from the United
States, Britain, Canada, France, Germany, Italy and Japan called on
commercial banks to play their part in the latest debt plan.
   ``We felt the banks should get on with the negotiations,'' said
Canadian Finance Minister Michael Wilson. ``We feel the resources
that are in place are adequate to do the job.''
   Toyoo Gyoten, deputy Japanese finance minister, said, ``The main
thrust was we have to continue to put the wind in the sails (of
bankers) and keep it moving.''
   In supporting the current approach, the officials turned aside
fresh pleas for more help from leaders of poorer nations, who were
in town to mark Friday's 200th anniversary of the French revolution.
   In their economic talks, summit participants were generally
upbeat about the economic outlook but warned of the threat posed by
rising inflation in some countries.
   ``There's no recession talk at all,'' said Wilson. ``There's no
country who saw a recession on the horizon or the possibility of a
recession on the horizon.''
   But, he said, ``Inflation is a problem we must continue to deal
with, that we must continue to be vigilant on.''
   The officials also stressed the importance of correcting the
budget and trade imbalances run up by some countries.
   They urged countries to make sure the current round of trade
liberalization end on a successful note by their scheduled 1990
deadline. The talks, under the auspices of the General Agreement on
Tariffs and Trade, have been hampered by disputes over agricultural
subsidies and other issues. The 96-nation GATT is a forum and
arrangement to promote free world trade.
   Much of the attention of the economic discussions has been
focused on Mexico's debt negotiations.
   Mexico is the developing world's No. 2 debtor, behind Brazil. It
has often taken the lead in finding new ways to ease the debt load.
   Sununu, showing his thumb and index finger nearly touching, said
Mexican officials and private bankers ``are now about that far
apart.''
   He said another bargaining session was expected ``in the next 24
hours or so. And it is hoped that at that meeting substantially most
of, if not all, of that gap will be closed.''
   Wilson also said the debt talks were ``pretty close.'' He said a
Mexican deal could ``clearly be an incentive to other countries'' to
make economic changes required for participation in the rich
countries' debt plan. It calls for debtor nations to cut inflation
rates, strengthen their currencies and take other steps to regain
their economic health.
   Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady said Friday the United States
was willing to work with the other industrialized nations to arrange
a $1 billion to $2 billion emergency loan to help Mexico meet its
obligations while it negotiates with private bankers for a new debt
accord.
   Mexico owes private lenders $54 billion, with about $15 billion
due American banks.
   In its negotiations with bankers, Mexico wants to slash both its
overall debt and the amount of its annual interest payments, which
run about $10 billion a year.
   Both sides have tentatively agreed on a 35 percent discount that
would mean savings to Mexico of about $3 billion in annual debt
payments, according to sources who demanded anonymity.
</TEXT>
