<FIRST>r i AM-BoyPilot     07-15 0170</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Boy Pilot,0176</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Boy Ends Flight Across Soviet Union</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 11-year-old American pilot completed his trip
across the Soviet Union on Saturday when he took off from the
Siberian town of Anadyr for Alaska, the official Soviet news agency
Tass said.
   Tony Aliengena, accompanied by his father and a Soviet pilot,
dealt with icy wings and flew through mountains at low altitude to
become the first private pilot to traverse Siberia, which stretches
across 12 time zones, Tass said.
   The boy from San Juan Capistrano, Calif., is trying to become the
youngest pilot to fly around the globe. Saturday's flight across the
Bering Strait to Nome will bring him back to his native land.
   But for the world record, he must still fly down the coast of
North America to California to return to his starting point in
Orange County, Calif.
   Also flying in his plane and in a second aircraft were his
mother, sister, a Russian pen pal and a documentary film crew.
</TEXT>
