<FIRST>u i AM-Summit-GoodIntentions 2ndLd-Writethru a0576 07-15 0699</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Summit-Good Intentions, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0576,720</SECOND>
<HEAD>Summit Statement Reflects Lack of Economic or Political Peril</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs. Restores dropped AP news analysis line</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Harmony and reverence for human rights echoed
Saturday from the summit document adopted by leaders of seven
democracies in a windowless room on the 35th floor of the Grand
Arch, France's newest national symbol.
   On the bicentennial of the French Revolution, it was only natural
that President Bush and his six partners reaffirmed their commitment
to freedom and democratic principles even as they pointedly urged
China to cease its repression of pro-democracy forces.
   But facing no immediate threats to their security or their
economies, the summiteers issued a mild communique.
   It thundered at terrorists without identifying their supporters.
   It skirted the oppressive hunger of the undernourished Third
World.
   And it pledged no cold cash for Poland and Hungary to smooth the
transition of the two Soviet bloc countries to free market economies.
   Even before the leaders opened their deliberations Friday evening
at a lavish dinner of stuffed lobster and lamb, washed down with
Chateau Montrose 1918, a tentative U.S. proposal to create a
``clearinghouse'' for aid to Poland and Hungary was jettisoned.
   At the last minute, West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl, working
in tandem with Bush, won approval for a conference of ``all
interested countries'' later this summer to consider Poland's urgent
food problems and ``concerted support for reform'' in the two
countries.
   Bush paved the way with letters to his summit partners before he
came to Paris. For now, Secretary of State James A. Baker III told
reporters, the site, agenda and participants in the aid-for-Poland
conference have not been determined.
   French President Francois Mitterrand, a Socialist host presiding
over a gathering of largely conservative leaders, found no support
for his proposal to set up an international conference with poor
countries to consider ways to ease their staggering $1.3 trillion
debt. Mitterrand had to abandon the idea.
   With some two dozen heads of Third World countries here as
bicentennial guests, the communique offered hopeful rhetoric _ but,
as expected, not much else.
   The section on China called on the World Bank to postpone new
loans as a way of registering ``our deep sense of condemnation''
over Beijing's repressive measures. Also, Chinese students
apprehensive about returning home were assured they could stay
indefinitely in the United States, Britain, Canada, France, Italy
and West Germany.
   No sanctions were recommended, an apparent ratification of Bush's
policy of taking a measured approach to events in Beijing. Baker
said the President had taken the lead on the subject at the summit.
   ``We look to the Chinese authorities to create conditions which
will avoid their isolation and provide for a return to cooperation
based upon the resumption of movement towards political and economic
reform and openness,'' the communique said with a diplomatic lack of
directness.
   And while the seven leaders encouraged ``greater freedom and
democracy'' in Central and Eastern Europe, they evinced no sign of
fervor or immediate aid to match U.S. incentives of $115 million and
$25 million that Bush extended to Poland and Hungary during his
visits there.
   Even so, Baker was pleased with the overall results. He said the
leaders got along so well they may be able to conclude their
deliberations ahead of schedule on Sunday.
   Having attended nine summits as White House chief of staff,
Treasury secretary and now secretary of state, Baker said this was
``the most harmonious and one of the most productive summits that I
have attended.''
   Bush, after breakfast Saturday with British Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher, dismissed the absence of specific aid commitments
from his summit partners.
   ``There have been some misconceptions we would come in here with
a dollar package,'' the president said. ``I managed to convey in
Poland that that was not the case and here it is not the case.''
   He said the communique ``vindicated'' his approach.
   Mrs. Thatcher said, meanwhile, ``We are all very anxious to help.
We are all helping, each in our own way.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Barry Schweid, chief of The Associated Press'
State Department staff, is covering his fifth economic summit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
