<FIRST>r i AM-Panama     07-15 0351</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panama,0360</SECOND>
<HEAD>OAS, In Third Mediation Effort, Pulls Military Into Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mediators from the Organization of
American States said Saturday that the government and opposition
leaders have agreed to hold talks to resolve Panama's political
crisis.
   A statement by the mission from the Organization of American
States said the talks were scheduled to begin Sunday ``without an
agenda, without preconditions and with the commitment that no topic
would be excluded.''
   The Defense Forces will send representatives to the talks as part
of the government delegation, the statement said. The Defense Forces
chief, Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, is the nation's de factor leader
and is under pressure to quit.
   Up to now, the position of the Defense Forces and the government
has been that Noriega's situation was not subject to discussion.
Saturday's announcement ``that no topic would be excluded'' seemed
to indicate a change of attitude.
   It will be the first time that the Defense Forces, government and
opposition have held talks.
   The OAS delegation arrived Saturday on its third mediation visit
since Noriega's regime annulled an election May 7 that international
observers say opposition candidates won by a landslide.
   Ecuador's Foreign Minister Diego Cordovez is heading the mission,
which includes foreign ministers Mario Palencia of Guatemala and
Sadeo Badseo of Trinidad-Tobago, and OAS Secretary-General Joao
Baena Soares of Brazil.
   Opposition presidential candidate Guillermo Endara, backed by a
coalition of his own Liberal Party, the Christian Democrats and the
Nationalist Liberal Republican Party, is demanding Noriega's ouster
and that the government admit it lost the election.
   The opposition also accuses Noriega of human rights violations,
corruption and press censorship.
   Noriega has been under pressure from the United States to step
down since two federal grand juries indicted him in Florida in
February 1988 on drug trafficking and money-laundering charges.
   Noriega has accused the United States of trying replace him with
a docile government that would agree to a continuation of a U.S.
military presence beyond Dec. 31, 1999, when the Panama Canal is to
be turned over to Panama.
</TEXT>
