<FIRST>r i AM-Peru-Rebels     07-15 0233</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Peru-Rebels,0239</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leftist Guerrillas Disable State Mine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist guerrillas attacked one of the largest
state-owned mines in the country, destroying machinery and forcing
suspension of operations for six months, police said Saturday.
   Two mine workers were reported wounded.
   About 100 guerrillas from the leftist Shining Path group attacked
the Morococha mine Friday, setting off dynamite that destroyed
mining machinery, fuel tanks, electrical generators and electronic
control panels, police said.
   The mine, owned by the state mining company Centromin-Peru,
produces copper, lead, zinc and silver. It is located in the Andean
highlands 70 miles northeast of Lima at more than 13,000 feet above
sea level in the department of Junin.
   Police in Huancayo, Junin's capital, said the guerrillas first
attacked the police station of Morococha with dynamite to prevent
officers from reaching the mine.
   Two mine workers who tried to repel the attack on the mine were
seriously wounded, the police said.
   Centromin-Peru employs about 17,000 miners, 3,000 of them at the
Morococha mine. The company brings in about $300 million a year to
this impoverished nation.
   The Shining Path has been battling Peru's elected government
since 1980. The government says more than 15,000 people have died in
the war.
   Mining companies have been asking officials for more protection
against terrorist attacks. Rebel groups often target the isolated
mining camps to hinder production and steal dynamite, food and
medicine.
</TEXT>
