<FIRST>r a AM-SunburnIndex     07-15 0368</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sunburn Index,0379</SECOND>
<HEAD>Weather Reports to Include Sunburn Index</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICE GRAVINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Weather forecasts here will have something new
beginning this week _ the ``scorch factor,'' which two local
physicians hope will remind folks of the dangers of skin cancer.
   With a shoebox-size device on the roof of a Baylor University
Medical Center building, Alan Menter and Chuck Phillips can
calculate how long it will take the sun's ultraviolet rays to start
burning unprotected skin.
   The physicians have begun reporting to the National Weather
Service ultraviolet readings at 10 a.m., noon and 3 p.m., along with
the number of minutes a sun-sensitive person can be exposed without
harm.
   One Dallas television station will add the roast quotient to its
evening weather reports starting Monday, and several other TV and
radio stations have expressed interest in the index.
   Similar reports are available through the weather service in
Tucson, Ariz., and Atlanta, Ga., Phillips said.
   ``We're trying to make people aware that there is a sun out there
that is doing damage to their skin,'' said Phillips, a medical
center internist who is switching to dermatology. Menter, a
dermatologist, is medical director of the Baylor Psoriasis Center.
   Texas has one of the highest rates of skin cancer in the country,
Phillips said.
   ``Of course, we're in the sun belt, and in the south you get more
ultraviolet exposure,'' he said. ``And because of the weather,
people tend to develop more of an outdoor lifestyle. So skin cancer
is a real problem.''
   He added that certain types of skin cancer can be fatal if not
treated early, and sun damage can also hasten the aging of the skin.
   People who stay outside longer than the index suggests _ usually
15 to 30 minutes on a sunny or partly-cloudy day _ should cover up
or apply sun screens, Phillips said.
   He added that weather can fool people. ``They equate heat with
sunburn, so they think August is going to be the peak'' in
ultraviolet radiation, he said. In fact, the ultraviolet rays peak
in June and July, then decline steadly to late December, when the
sun is farthest away from the Northern Hemisphere, Phillips said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
