<SECOND>AM-North's Notebooks, 1st Add,270</SECOND>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING a0525 to adjust coding in slug line</HEAD>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON: days earlier</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Portions of the censored versions of the notebooks which North
handed over to Congress played a role in recently ended Senate
confirmation hearings for Donald Gregg, President Bush's
ambassadorial nominee to South Korea. Gregg was Bush's national
security affairs adviser when he was vice president.
   At a June 15 hearing, Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif., and Sen. John
Kerry, D-Mass., focused on a meeting of Bush, Gregg and former CIA
operative Felix Rodriguez on Jan. 24, 1985.
   North's notebooks contain several references to Rodriguez the
week of the Jan. 24, 1985, meeting, but North's lawyers blacked out
most of the detailed notes adjacent to the references to Rodriguez,
saying they were irrelevant to Congress' Iran-Contra inquiries.
   ``I think it's absolutely clear that North and Rodriguez were
setting up an illicit Contra aid operation the very same week that
Gregg and Rodriguez met to discuss Felix's desire to help in Central
America,'' Cranston said at the hearing. Kerry said the notebooks
should be produced in uncensored form.
   The Bush-Gregg-Rodriguez meeting took place as Rodriguez prepared
to leave for El Salvador, where he ended up assisting North's secret
resupply operation to the Contras at a time when Congress had banned
military aid to the rebel force.
   Gregg, who paved the way with U.S. officials for his longtime
friend Rodriguez to go to El Salvador, says he didn't know until
August 1986 that Rodriguez was assisting the Contras.
   Gregg says Rodriguez' mission was to assist the Salvadoran Air
Force, not the Contras, and that the Jan. 24, 1985, meeting with
Bush didn't touch on the Nicaraguan rebels.
