<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0399</SECOND>
<HEAD>Storms Soak Kansas, Missouri</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms spattered heavy rain on parts of northeast Kansas
and northwest Missouri on Saturday, flooding streets in the Kansas
City area.
   Heavy rain fell from Topeka to Kansas City, 60 miles to the east.
More than 2 inches of rain fell in one hour at Kansas City
International Airport.
   Flooding from heavy rains also occurred Saturday morning in the
northeast Texas counties of Delta, Hopkins and Hunt.
   Rain and scattered thunderstorms extended from southeast
Minnesota and southwest Wisconsin along the Mississippi Valley to
the Gulf Coast. Showers and thunderstorms also rumbled across the
Gulf Coast and South Atlantic coastal states. Columbia, S.C., had
more than 1{ inches of rain in one hour Saturday.
   In the West, an area of low pressure extended from the desert
Southwest across Nevada to Idaho. Unstable air produced
thunderstorms across portions of eastern Washington, Idaho and
extreme western Montana.
   Thunderstorms developed Saturday afternoon over southwest Texas
and across the New Mexico and Colorado Rockies.
   A high pressure system across the Northeast, however, kept the
region dry Saturday.
   Heavier rainfall during the six hours ending at 2 p.m. EDT
included more than 1{ inches at Topeka, El Dorado, Ariz., and
Columbia.
   Temperatures at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 59 degrees at Oak Harbor,
Wash., to 104 degrees at Gila Bend, Ariz., and Phoenix. The low in
the Lower 48 on Saturday was 30 degrees at Truckee, Calif.
   The forecast for Sunday called for scattered thunderstorms from
the middle and south Atlantic Coast states across the Tennessee
Valley and the Gulf coastal states to portions of the southern
Plains; and scattered showers and thunderstorms from the lower Ohio
Valley across the middle and upper Mississippi Valley to Upper
Michigan. Scattered thunderstorms were to develop over western
portions of the Plains, the Rocky Mountains and the northern plateau
region. Rain was expected to develop on the Washington coast.
   Predicted high temperatures were in the 60s and 70s along the
Pacific Coast and across Washington state; 70s from portions of the
upper and middle Mississippi Valley across the Great Lakes region
and the northern half of the Appalachians to New England; 100s in
portions of south-central and southwest Texas and some sections of
Utah; 100 to 115 degrees in the desert Southwest; and 80s and 90s
elsewhere.
