<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Subs     07-15 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Subs,0346</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Officer Says All Golf II Submarines to Leave Baltic</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   All Soviet Golf II submarines, which
carry nuclear weapons, will be removed from the Baltic Sea early
next year, a Soviet naval commander was quoted as saying in an
interview published Saturday.
   General Staff officer Alexander Rudenko told the Dagens Nyheter
daily newspaper that the Soviet Union also would dislcose whether
its warships were carrying nuclear weapons if they were invited to a
Swedish port.
   Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev previously had talked of
scrapping the dated Golf II submarines in the Baltic fleet, but he
gave no date.
   The submarines, which date to the 1960s, are 325 feet long. Each
carries three missile tubes, according to Jane's Fighting Ships.
   The Soviet Baltic fleet has six to eight vessels armed with
intermediate-range missiles.
   ``All Soviet nuclear submarines of the Golf II class will be
removed from the Baltic Sea at the beginning of next year,'' Dagens
Nyheter quoted Rudenko as saying. ``Now we only wait for the United
States to show its good intent.''
   A Swedish defense spokeman declined to say if the Soviet Union
has other types of nuclear submarines in the Baltic. He said no
Soviet ship has made a port call in Sweden in about 25 years.
   NATO ships refuse as a matter of policy to say whether they are
carrying nuclear weapons. All the Scandinavian countries have
policies banning nuclear weapons in their ports.
   ``If our aircraft carrier Kiev, which has nuclear weapons on
board, would be invited by Sweden,'' Rudenko was quoted as saying,
``we would leave the nuclear weapons at home before coming to
visit.''
   Rudenko was identified by the paper as an officer responsible for
peace and disarmament issues at the Soviet General Staff. Officials
at the Soviet Embassy declined to comment or expand on the report.
   Rudenko was in Sweden on Friday to participate in a Nordic youth
trip to the Soviet naval base in Murmansk on the Kola Peninsula.
</TEXT>
