<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Blast     07-15 0164</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Blast,0172</SECOND>
<HEAD>Months Needed to Restore Refinery After Blast</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It will be several months before a natural gas
refinery that exploded in flames last week will return to full
operations, state television said Saturday.
   Four people were killed and six injured in Wednesday's blast and
fire at the refinery in Almetyevsk in central Russia. The evening
news show Vremya said Saturday that houses in the nearby village of
Makhtama also were damaged.
   A government inquiry blamed the explosion on a propane gas leak,
the official news agency Tass said earlier.
   Almetyevsk is about 500 miles east of Moscow in the Tatar
Autonomous Republic.
   The republic's deputy premier, M.G. Sabirov, told Vremya it will
take several months to repair damage at the refinery.
   News reports did not indicate if the accident would affect Soviet
gas exports.
   Last month, a gas pipeline leaked and exploded as two passenger
trains were passing in the Soviet Ural Mountains. More than 600
people were killed.
</TEXT>
