<FIRST>r a AM-ErrantFlight     07-15 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Errant Flight,0368</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leisurely Flight Ends With Landing at Stealth Base, Pilot's Arrest</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Stealth Test, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LANCASTER, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A misguided Cessna 182 turned out to be
the only show in town for thousands of people gathered for the first
flight of the B-2 stealth bomber Saturday. The Cessna, at least, got
off the ground.
   Brian Green, a 35-year-old schoolteacher from Porterville,
apparently got lost over the Mojave Desert while out for spin with
his niece and nephew, Kris and Sarah Erickson, authorities said.
   He landed the rented plane on the tarmac of Air Force Plant 42
just as the stealth bomber was ready to taxi for its maiden flight.
While the children watched aghast, security agents swooped in and
frisked and handcuffed Green.
   ``We just got lost,'' said Kris, 9.``My uncle was being arrested
and we were right with him and it was scary.''
   ``They flew down to pick me up in Agua Dulce. They made a slight
detour, I guess,'' said the youngsters' father, Steve Erickson of
Santa Clarita. Agua Dulce is about 10 miles southwest of the air
base in Palmdale, which neighbors Lancaster.
   Green received his pilot's license three years ago and it was the
first time he had attempted the flight from Tulare Airport in
central California to Agua Dulce in the southern part of the state,
said Erickson, who picked up his children at a Los Angeles County
sheriff's substation here.
   Sheriff's Lt. Tom Pigott said Green was booked for investigation
of misdemeanor trespassing and was later released on his own
recognizance.
   ``Mr. Green was very cooperative at the scene and he gave his
consent for the plane to be searched and nothing unusual or
subversive was found,'' said Pigott, who was on the tarmac as part
of the security force.
   As it turned out, a low fuel gauge reading prompted officials to
postpone Saturday's planned flight of the B-2, disappointing
thousands of aviation buffs who gathered outside the air base.
   The unexpected arrival of the stray Cessna played no role in the
decision to scrub the flight, said Air Force Col. Douglas Kennett.
</TEXT>
