<FIRST>r a AM-SecondAbduction     07-15 0282</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Second Abduction,0288</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gag Order, Change of Venue, Sought in Paula Sims Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EDWARDSVILLE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An attorney for a woman charged with
killing her 6-week-old daughter and claiming the infant was abducted
has asked for a gag order and change of venue for the woman's trial.
   Paula Sims is also accused of concealing the 1986 death of her
first daughter, 13-day-old Loralei, whom she reported abducted under
circumstances similar to the disappearance of 6-week-old Heather in
April.
   After a hearing Friday on other charges against Mrs. Sims in
Heather's death, attorney Donald E. Groshong filed motions asking
that the murder trial be moved from Madison County because of news
coverage. He's also seeking to have police and prosecutors barred
from publicly discussing the case.
   A ruling on the motions is expected at a hearing scheduled July
21 on the murder charge against Mrs. Sims.
   Mrs. Sims, 30, has denied any wrongdoing.
   At Friday's hearing, Madison County Associate Judge Ellar
Duffwilliams ordered Mrs. Sims to stand trial on charges of
obstructing justice and concealing Heather's death. Mrs. Sims was
charged with murder in that death on Tuesday.
   In the case of both disappearences, Mrs. Sims reported that a
masked gunman abducted the baby girls while her husband, Robert, was
away at work. Police say they have found no evidence to support her
assertion and consider the couple the prime suspects.
   Robert Sims has not been charged in either case, and the only
murder charge against his wife is in Heather's death. An autopsy
showed that Heather's body had been frozen before it was dumped in a
trash can on May 3, four days after Mrs. Sims reported her daughter
kidnapped.
</TEXT>
