<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-89 2038EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-BareBreasts     07-15 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bare Breasts,0264</SECOND>
<HEAD>Seventeen Women Bare Breasts in Protest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SENECA FALLS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of 17 women bared their breasts
in front of the national Women's Hall of Fame on Saturday to protest
a state law that prohibits women from going shirtless in public.
   The women marched to the museum and gave speeches before taking
off their shirts in front of about 200 people during an annual
convention commemorating the birth of the women's movement here.
   Local police and state troopers stood by during the
demonstration, but no arrests were made. The women bared their
breasts for about two minutes, then put their shirts back on and
left.
   The protest came nearly three weeks after ten members of the
group were arrested in Rochester for baring their breasts on a
beach. They're scheduled to appear in city court on Aug. 1 to answer
charges of exposure of person, a violation, to which they've pleaded
innocent.
   Ramona Santorelli, one of the women who participated in the
protest, said the group, called the Coalition for Topfree Equality,
wanted to make the statement that rules against shirtless women were
discriminatory.
   ``I think that people are making the connection, the deeper
issues. We're not just exposing our breasts. We're exposing the
sexual issues, the inequality,'' Santorelli said.
   Santorelli said an agreement had been made with the Seneca Falls
chief of police that he would give the group two warnings before
making any arrests.
   A spokeswoman at the Hall of Fame said the museum had no
connection with the women.
</TEXT>
