<FIRST>r a AM-BRF--RobberMugged     07-15 0194</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Robber Mugged,0199</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bank Robber Gets Mugged, Reports Both Crimes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who allegedly stole $2,100 from a bank was
mugged as he fled the bank, then walked into a police station to
report both robberies, police said.
   Anthony Colella, 49, entered the Independence Savings Bank in
Brooklyn on Friday, police said, and handed a teller a note saying,
``Be fast. I have a gun. ... Give me all your money. ... Don't make
me pull it.''
   The teller gave him $2,100, which Colella put in a paper bag
before fleeing on foot, police said. Moments later, he was thrown to
the ground by a man who took the money and fled in a station wagon,
said Detective Sgt. Timothy Dowd.
   Colella went to the local precinct. ``The suspect surrendered to
the desk lieutenant and implicated himself in the bank robbery,''
Dowd said, and provided a description of his attacker.
   ``Only a psychiatrist would know why he did it,'' said another
police spokesman, Sgt. Norris Hollomon.
   Colella was charged with first-degree robbery and criminal
possession of stolen property and a weapon. The station wagon mugger
has not been found.
</TEXT>
