<FIRST>u i AM-Chile-Mormons     07-15 0303</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chile-Mormons,0317</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gunmen Set Fire to Mormon Chapel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDUARDO GALLARDO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LA FLORIDA, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two attackers raided a Mormon chapel in
this Santiago suburb Saturday, set it on fire and left pamphlets of
a leftist guerrilla group, authorities said.
   No one was injured in the attack, the second this month on a
Mormon chapel in La Florida.
   In the previous attack on July 7, seven assailants interrupted a
chapel gathering, forced the missionary to undress and then fled. No
one was injured; church officials later said the attackers may have
wanted simply to humiliate the missionary.
   Police said they have made no arrests in either attack.
   Leftist guerrillas have a history of making such attacks in
recent years. They say the Mormon Church, based in Salt Lake City,
Utah, is a force for U.S. imperialism.
   In Saturday's predawn attack, the two men brandished pistols and
told the watchman Celestino Gonzalez, ``This is a robbery,''
Gonzalez said.
   However, he said, they then poured a flammable liquid on the
wooden chapel, which is about 40 feet long, and set it on fire
before fleeing. Gonzalez said he put out the fire himself.
   The pamphlets the attackers left behind were from a small group
of urban radicals known as the Lautaro Rebel Front.
   That same group claimed responsibility for the earlier attack in
La Florida.
   The Mormon Church in Chile had no immediate comment on Saturday's
attack.
   A church spokesman said after earlier incidents that most of the
approximately 250 Mormon missionaries in the country are Chilean. He
said only a very small number are American.
   In May in La Paz, Bolivia, two Mormon missionaries from Utah were
shot and killed as they returned to their apartment. A group known
as the Armed Liberation Front of Zarate Willka claimed
responsibility.
</TEXT>
