<FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-89 2313EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-HUD-D.C.     07-15 0380</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-HUD-D.C.,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>D.C., Maryland Housing Officials Say Developers Boasted Inside Track
to HUD</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State and local housing officials in and around
the nation's capital say developers increasingly asserted they had
connections in the Reagan administration that would guarantee scarce
federal housing funds, a published report says.
   ``They'd say, if D.C. needs the units, this is the only way to
get them,'' said Alphonso Jackson, public housing director for the
District of Columbia in 1987 and 1988.
   ``I said, `I will not put the city manager or the mayor in a
position to be haunted by this,''' Jackson told The Washington Post.
   Sunday's edition of The Post reports that developers seeking
funds through the Department of Housing and Urban Development's
moderate rehabiltation program often dropped the names of
high-ranking government officials like then-assistant secretary for
housing Thomas Demery, and former Interior Secretary James Watt.
   Several federal housing programs have been under scrutiny by HUD,
the Justice Department and Congress for alleged mismanagement and
fraud.
   ``It was public knowledge that if you were wired in as a
Republican, you got funding,'' Jackson told the newspaper.
   He said local housing directors, the mayors or the city councils
shouldn't be blamed because ``they figure they may not be following
the rules, but they are addressing the need.''
   Trudy McFall, Maryland's communiy development administrator, said
there was no question that the state received funds that had been
steered.
   Under the moderate rehabilitation program, local housing
authorities, not individual developers, were to apply to federal
funds. Developers then were to offer competitive proposals for
project funding.
   However, McFall said developer Judith Siegel correctly told her
of changes in HUD procedures in 1987 that would qualify Maryland for
previously denied funds. Siegel told her of the changes before HUD
notified the state, McFall said.
   McFall said Siegel claimed she received her information from
Demery.
   Siegel, who the newspaper said could not be reached for comment,
has testified before a congressional subcommittee that she paid Watt
$300,000 in consulting fees for the Kingsley Park development
project in Essex, Md. Both Watt and Seigel said their actions were
legal.
   The HUD inspector general in April issued a highly critical
report saying top HUD officials created a ``perception'' of
favoritism in the moderate rehabilitation program.
</TEXT>
