<TEXT>
   The fate of Paramount Communications Inc.'s
hostile $12.2 billion bid for Time Inc. rests with the Delaware
Supreme Court after a judge refused to block Time's $14 billion
tender offer for Warner Communications Inc.
   The Supreme Court agreed late Friday to hear the case after
Chancery Court Judge William T. Allen turned down a request by
Paramount and some of Time's biggest shareholders for an injunction
against Time's bid for Warner.
   Allen halted Time's $70 a share offer, which had been scheduled
to expire at midnight Monday, for 10 days to give Paramount time to
appeal his ruling. If Paramount loses, it will pave the way for Time
and Warner to merge, forming Time Warner Inc., the world's largest
communications concern.
   Paramount, which is offering $200 a share for Time, has said it
would not pursue a buyout of Time Warner.
