<FIRST>a f BC-Week'sBusiness Adv15-16 1stLd-Writethru 07-15 0665</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Week's Business, Adv 15-16, 1st Ld-Writethru,0683</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv15</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv16</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release weekend editions July 15-16</HEAD>
<HEAD>From BAT to Batman: Billions and Billions in Deals</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 7th graf pvs to UPDATE with Paramount appeal; PICKS UP
8th graf pvs, `In Britain...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   BAT and Batman were at the center of two
multibillion-dollar takeover deals that took shape on opposite sides
of the Atlantic, one in the City of London and the other in Gotham
City.
   Overseas, a group led by British raider Sir James Goldsmith made
a $21.2 billion debt-financed hostile foray for BAT Industries PLC,
a conglomerate that owns the swank Saks Fifth Avenue chain and makes
Kool cigarettes.
   The offer, which affirms the migration of the American big buyout
to Europe, would amount to the second-largest deal in history behind
the $25 billion debt-financed takeover of RJR Nabisco Corp. earlier
this year.
   But if the recent history of American hostile takeovers is any
indication, this deal will go the way of all others: to court.
   That's where the protracted tussle over the future of New
York-based giants Time Inc., Paramount Communications Corp. and
Warner Communications Inc. is mired, and a judge on Friday helped
clear some of the sludge.
   Ruling on the side of Time's friendly $14 billion offer for
Warner _ the entertainment empire reaping big profits from its
``Batman'' film hit _ Delaware Chancery Court Judge William T. Allen
scuttled for now Paramount's hostile $12.2 billion offer for Time.
   The judge refused to block Time's $70-a-share offer. Paramount,
though, appealed the ruling to the state supreme court in Delaware,
where all three companies are incorporated.
   In Britain, BAT and its pursuer, a trio of powerful investors led
by Goldsmith, were lining up attorneys for what promises to be a
legal extravaganza.
   Since many BAT subsidiaries are American, the takeover could be
decided in U.S. courts. Earlier this year, a federal judge
effectively ended South Africa-controlled Minorco SA's bid for
Britain's Consolidated Gold Fields PLC by issuing a retraining order
against the acquisition.
   Besides highly paid investment bankers, the BAT offering would
bring two other popular American financial tools to Europe: the use
of high-yield junk bonds and the dismemberment of a large company.
   No caped crusader he, Goldsmith says he wants to bust up BAT by
selling its non-tobacco interests, which account for about 60
percent of its annual revenue of $28.7 billion. In America, those
interests include Saks, Marshall Field, Appleton Papers and Farmers
Group Inc., one of the nation's largest insurers.
   While the takeover gulf between Europe and the United States
appears to be narrowing, there's no denying the enormous economic
gap between East and West reflected in the BAT and Time capers.
   As the two deals went their respective routes _ Time in court,
BAT heading there _ President Bush was behind the Iron Curtain
offering Poland $100 million in aid, a figure that probably won't
approach the fees for lawyers and investment bankers in the takeover
bids.
   In other business news this week:
   _One of Chicago's commodities exchanges was back in the public
eye but the reason was soybeans, not FBI surveillance. The Chicago
Board of Trade issued an emergency order to curb trading in soybean
futures contracts amid rumors an Italian company was trying to
corner the market. A federal judge upheld the order but the Italians
said they will sue to recover losses.
   _More evidence emerged that the economy is contracting. Wholesale
prices fell 0.1 percent in June, the first drop in 18 months, retail
sales fell for the second straight month and the operating rate for
U.S. factories declined, government reports showed.
   _Leaders of the world's seven richest democracies gathered in
Paris during the bicentennial of the French Revolution for their
annual economic summit. President Bush won one victory in a trade
dispute but was thwarted in an attempt to engineer a deal to lower
Mexico's debt.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End advance for weekend editions July 15-16</NOTE>
</DOC>
